{"title_page": "Drawing the Line (play)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''''Drawing the Line''''' is a 2013 play by [[Howard Brenton]], centred on [[Cyril Radcliffe]] and his part in the [[partition of India]]. It premiered from 3 December 2013 to 11 January 2014, in a production directed by [[Howard Davies (director)|Howard Davies]] at London's [[Hampstead Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=What's On: Drawing the Line|publisher = [[Hampstead Theatre]] |url=http://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2013/drawing-the-line/|date = 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Storyline==\n\nThe play tells the story of Cyril Radcliffe and the boundary commission for the [[Punjab]] portion of the eponymous [[Radcliffe Line]]. \u201cIgnorant of India, mathematics or map-reading, the principled Radcliffe finds himself the victim of despair, as well as Delhi belly, and enmeshed in a whole series of escalating conflicts.\u201d<ref name = \"Billington\">{{cite web|title= Guardian Review of Drawing the Line |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/dec/10/drawing-the-line-review|title=Drawing the Line \u2013 review |author = [[Michael Billington (critic) |Billington, Michael]]|date = 10 December 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production history==\n\nThe debut run of the play was completely sold out. Thousands of people from more than 80 countries also tuned in to watch the final performance streamed on the web in association with  ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name = \"Shenton\">{{cite news|author= Shenton, Mark|title= Howard Brenton's Drawing the Line To Be Live-Streamed from London's Hampstead Theatre at Final Performance|work = [[Playbill]]|url=https://www.playbill.com/article/howard-brentons-drawing-the-line-to-be-live-streamed-from-londons-hampstead-theatre-at-final-performance-com-213500|date = 7 January 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\nCritical reviews<ref>{{cite news|title= Drawing the Line, Hampstead \u2013 theatre review |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/drawing-the-line-hampstead--theatre-review-8994665.html|work= [[Evening Standard]]|location= London|date = 10 December 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> were generally positive though there were critiques of some embellishments to the story. Compliments included \"brilliantly staged\",<ref name = \"Sierz\">{{cite web|title=Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre  |url=http://www.theartsdesk.com/theatre/drawing-line-hampstead-theatre|website= [[The Arts Desk]]|author= Sierz, Aleks| date = 10 December 2013| accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> \"absorbing\",<ref name = \"Sadler\">{{cite news|author= Sadler, Victoria|title=Theatre Review: Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/victoria-sadler/drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre_b_4425431.html|date = 10 February 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> and \"giv[ing] a vivid picture of the pressures of the time\".<ref name =\"Billington\"/> Criticisms included that the play \"fails to soar\"<ref>{{cite news|author= Orr, Jake|title= Review: Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre| url=http://www.ayoungertheatre.com/review-drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre-howard-brenton/|work= [[A Younger Theatre]]|date = 10 December 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> and \"brushes the boundaries of caricature\".<ref name = \"Cavendish\">{{cite news|title=Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/10508466/Drawing-the-Line-Hampstead-Theatre-review.html|author= Cavendish, Dominic|work = [[The Daily Telegraph]]|date = 10 December 2013||accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Louise Burns, reviewing the online screening in April 2020 of the 2014 production, said: \"Tom Hatley\u2019s clever set design uses tall, patterned wood partitions to indicate a world of India and aside from strategically placed desks, chairs and props the space is sparse, allowing the story to unfold through precise acting and sharply constructed dialogue.\"<ref name=\"Burns\">{{Cite news |last=Burns |first=Louise |url=https://www.thereviewshub.com/drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre-at-home/ |title=Drawing The Line\u2014 Hampstead Theatre At Home |date=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Reviews Hub]] |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayal of historical figures==\nAs [[Lord Mountbatten]], \"Andrew Havill gets beneath the cold, defender of the realm, exterior to eventually present him in a more human light, as a man with weaknesses and vulnerabilities that lead to him believing resolving his personal problems was justification for resorting to political expedience when everything else would tell him otherwise.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Public Reviews: Drawing the Line|url=http://www.thepublicreviews.com/drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre-london/|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a live webchat, Howard Brenton answered questions about his acclaimed play and his career. Defending his portrayal of Cyril Radcliffe as a man who struggled with his conscience, Brenton said \u201cThere were clues that Radcliffe had a dark night of the soul in the bungalow: he refused to accept his fee, he did collect all the papers and draft maps, took them home to England and burnt them. And he refused to say a word, even to his family, about what happened. My playwright\u2019s brain went into overdrive when I discovered these details.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|title=Live web chat with Howard Brenton|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/jan/07/live-stream-howard-brenton-drawing-the-line|author=Wiegand, Chris|work = [[The Guardian]]|date = 14 January 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2013/drawing-the-line/ Official website]\n\n{{Howard Brenton}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in theatre]]\n[[Category:2013 plays]]\n[[Category:English political plays]]\n[[Category:Historical plays]]\n[[Category:Partition of India in fiction]]\n[[Category:Plays by Howard Brenton]]\n[[Category:Plays set in India]]\n[[Category:Plays set in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''''Drawing the Line''''' is a 2013 play by [[Howard Brenton]], centred on [[Cyril Radcliffe]] and his part in the [[partition of India]]. It premiered from 3 December 2013 to 11 January 2014, in a production directed by [[Howard Davies (director)|Howard Davies]] at London's [[Hampstead Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=What's On: Drawing the Line|publisher = [[Hampstead Theatre]] |url=http://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2013/drawing-the-line/|date = 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Storyline==\n\nThe play tells the story of Cyril Radcliffe and the boundary commission for the [[Punjab]] portion of the eponymous [[Radcliffe Line]]. \u201cIgnorant of India, mathematics or map-reading, the principled Radcliffe finds himself the victim of despair, as well as Delhi belly, and enmeshed in a whole series of escalating conflicts.\u201d<ref name = \"Billington\">{{cite web|title= Guardian Review of Drawing the Line |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/dec/10/drawing-the-line-review|title=Drawing the Line \u2013 review |author = [[Michael Billington (critic) |Billington, Michael]]|date = 10 December 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production history==\n\nThe debut run of the play was completely sold out. Thousands of people from more than 80 countries also tuned in to watch the final performance streamed on the web in association with  ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name = \"Shenton\">{{cite news|author= Shenton, Mark|title= Howard Brenton's Drawing the Line To Be Live-Streamed from London's Hampstead Theatre at Final Performance|work = [[Playbill]]|url=https://www.playbill.com/article/howard-brentons-drawing-the-line-to-be-live-streamed-from-londons-hampstead-theatre-at-final-performance-com-213500|date = 7 January 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\nCritical reviews<ref>{{cite news|title= Drawing the Line, Hampstead \u2013 theatre review |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/drawing-the-line-hampstead--theatre-review-8994665.html|work= [[Evening Standard]]|location= London|date = 10 December 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> were generally positive though there were critiques of some embellishments to the story. Compliments included \"brilliantly staged\",<ref name = \"Sierz\">{{cite web|title=Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre  |url=http://www.theartsdesk.com/theatre/drawing-line-hampstead-theatre|website= [[The Arts Desk]]|author= Sierz, Aleks| date = 10 December 2013| accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> \"absorbing\",<ref name = \"Sadler\">{{cite news|author= Sadler, Victoria|title=Theatre Review: Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/victoria-sadler/drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre_b_4425431.html|date = 10 February 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> and \"giv[ing] a vivid picture of the pressures of the time\".<ref name =\"Billington\"/> Criticisms included that the play \"fails to soar\"<ref>{{cite news|author= Orr, Jake|title= Review: Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre| url=http://www.ayoungertheatre.com/review-drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre-howard-brenton/|work= [[A Younger Theatre]]|date = 10 December 2013|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> and \"brushes the boundaries of caricature\".<ref name = \"Cavendish\">{{cite news|title=Drawing the Line, Hampstead Theatre, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/10508466/Drawing-the-Line-Hampstead-Theatre-review.html|author= Cavendish, Dominic|work = [[The Daily Telegraph]]|date = 10 December 2013||accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Louise Burns, reviewing the online screening in April 2020 of of the 2014 production, said: \"Tom Hatley\u2019s clever set design uses tall, patterned wood partitions to indicate a world of India and aside from strategically placed desks, chairs and props the space is sparse, allowing the story to unfold through precise acting and sharply constructed dialogue.\"<ref name=\"Burns\">{{Cite news |last=Burns |first=Louise |url=https://www.thereviewshub.com/drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre-at-home/ |title=Drawing The Line\u2014 Hampstead Theatre At Home |date=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Reviews Hub]] |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayal of historical figures==\nAs [[Lord Mountbatten]], \"Andrew Havill gets beneath the cold, defender of the realm, exterior to eventually present him in a more human light, as a man with weaknesses and vulnerabilities that lead to him believing resolving his personal problems was justification for resorting to political expedience when everything else would tell him otherwise.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Public Reviews: Drawing the Line|url=http://www.thepublicreviews.com/drawing-the-line-hampstead-theatre-london/|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a live webchat, Howard Brenton answered questions about his acclaimed play and his career. Defending his portrayal of Cyril Radcliffe as a man who struggled with his conscience, Brenton said \u201cThere were clues that Radcliffe had a dark night of the soul in the bungalow: he refused to accept his fee, he did collect all the papers and draft maps, took them home to England and burnt them. And he refused to say a word, even to his family, about what happened. My playwright\u2019s brain went into overdrive when I discovered these details.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|title=Live web chat with Howard Brenton|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/jan/07/live-stream-howard-brenton-drawing-the-line|author=Wiegand, Chris|work = [[The Guardian]]|date = 14 January 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2013/drawing-the-line/ Official website]\n\n{{Howard Brenton}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in theatre]]\n[[Category:2013 plays]]\n[[Category:English political plays]]\n[[Category:Historical plays]]\n[[Category:Partition of India in fiction]]\n[[Category:Plays by Howard Brenton]]\n[[Category:Plays set in India]]\n[[Category:Plays set in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drawing_the_Line_(play)"}
{"title_page": "Bloodshot (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 film directed by David S. F. Wilson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Bloodshot\n| image          = File:Bloodshot - official film poster.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = David S. F. Wilson\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Neal H. Moritz]]\n* Toby Jaffe\n* Dinesh Shamdasani\n* [[Vin Diesel]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jeff Wadlow]]\n* [[Eric Heisserer]]\n}}\n| story          = Jeff Wadlow\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Bloodshot (comics)|Bloodshot]]|[[Kevin VanHook]]|[[Don Perlin]]|[[Bob Layton]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Vin Diesel]]\n* [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n* [[Sam Heughan]]\n* [[Toby Kebbell]]\n* [[Guy Pearce]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Steve Jablonsky]]\n| cinematography = Jacques Jouffret\n| editing        = Jim May\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Bona Film Group]]\n* [[Cross Creek Pictures]]\n* Annabell Pictures\n* The Hideaway Entertainment\n* [[Original Film]]\n* [[One Race Films]]\n* [[Valiant Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|3|13|United States}}\n| runtime        = 109 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $45\nmillion<ref name=BOM/>\n| gross          = $29.2 million<ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Bloodshot-(2020)#tab=summary |title=Bloodshot (2020) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl235374081/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |title=Bloodshot (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Bloodshot''''' is a 2020 American [[superhero film]] based on the [[Valiant Comics]] character [[Bloodshot (comics)|of the same name]]. It is intended to be the first installment in a series of films set within a Valiant Comics [[Shared universe|shared cinematic universe]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/valiant-entertainment-is-jumping-from-comics-to-movies-and-tv-2019-9 |title=How Valiant Entertainment is jumping from comics to movies and TV |author=Travis Clark |date=September 18, 2019 |website=Business Insider}}</ref> Directed by David S. F. Wilson (in his feature directorial debut) from a screenplay by [[Jeff Wadlow]] and [[Eric Heisserer]] and a story by Wadlow,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://findawriter.wgaeast.org/project/1156287/bloodshot/ |title=Bloodshot |website=WGA Directory}}</ref> the film stars [[Vin Diesel]], [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Sam Heughan]], [[Toby Kebbell]], and [[Guy Pearce]]. It follows a Marine who was killed in action, only to be brought back to life with superpowers by an organization that wants to use him as a weapon.\n\nDevelopment of a Bloodshot film began in 2012, with [[Jared Leto]] originally in talks to star in July 2017. In March 2018, Diesel was hired to portray the title role, and the rest of the cast joined over the following months. Filming commenced in South Africa in August 2018, lasting through October.\n\n''Bloodshot'' was theatrically released in the United States on March 13, 2020, by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]. The film received mixed reviews from critics and has grossed $29 million worldwide. Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] closing theaters across the globe, Sony made the film available digitally on-demand less than two weeks after it was released theatrically.\n\n==Plot==\nAfter leading a successful rescue operation in [[Mombasa]], U.S. Airman Ray Garrison and his wife Gina travel for a holiday at an Italian beachside town in the [[Amalfi Coast]]. However, they are kidnapped by a group of mercenaries led by Martin Axe, who demands to know the source of the Mombasa hostage operation. Since Ray is not privy to this information, Axe kills him and Gina.\n\nRay is later resurrected by Rising Spirit Tech, a company that specializes in developing cybernetic enhancements for disabled US military personnel. The company's CEO, Dr. Emil Harting, tells Ray that he is the first successful candidate that they have resurrected using a [[nanorobotics|special nanite technology]]. Ray is also introduced to Dr Harting's other patients including former [[United States Navy|US Navy]] diver \"KT\", whom he strikes a friendship with, and former soldiers Jimmy Dalton and Marcus Tibbs, with whom he gets on poorly.\n\nAfter experiencing \"flashbacks\" of Gina and Axe, Ray escapes Rising Spirit's laboratory in [[Kuala Lumpur]] and pursues Axe, seeking to avenge Gina's death. Using the nanites to hack into computer databases, Ray tracks down Axe to [[Budapest]]. After trapping his convoy in a tunnel, Ray kills Axe's bodyguards before executing the mercenary. He is later recovered by KT, Dalton and Tibbs, who bring him back to Rising Spirit for reprogramming. In truth, Harting created false memories of Gina's death as part of a plot to eliminate rivals in Rising Spirit.\n\nAfter his memories are wiped and reprogrammed, Ray is sent to kill Nick Baris in [[East Sussex]], \"remembering\" him to be Gina's killer. Though Ray manages to kill Baris and his bodyguards, Baris has forced computer programmer Wilfred Wigans to build an [[electromagnetic pulse|EMP bomb]], which is ignited after Baris' death, incapacitating Ray and severing communications with Rising Spirit. After \"resurrecting\" Ray, Wigans reveals that Rising Spirit planted false memories to turn him into a killing machine. Ray also discovers Gina is alive but had left him five years ago and started a family in [[Westminster]].\n\nGrowing disillusioned with Harting's exploitation of Ray, KT seeks Wigans' help in taking him down. Meanwhile, Ray is recaptured by Dalton and Tibbs following a pursuit. He is brought back to Rising Spirit's laboratory for reprogramming, but escapes with the help of KT and Wigans, who sabotage the reprogramming process and Rising Spirit's computers. Breaking free, Ray fights Dalton and Tibbs on top of an elevator. Dalton willingly lets Tibbs fall to his death before continuing the fight until Ray punches him down the elevator shaft, killing him. Ray confronts Harting, who manages to drain the nanites, but is killed when the second grenade he shoots at Ray is dismantled by the nanites and dropped directly at his feet. Ray is later rebuilt by Wigans and KT, and the three then leave in search of a new life.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vin Diesel]] as [[Bloodshot (comics)|Ray Garrison / Bloodshot]]\n* [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]] as KT\n* [[Sam Heughan]] as Jimmy Dalton\n* [[Toby Kebbell]] as Martin Axe\n* [[Guy Pearce]] as Dr. Emil Harting\n* [[Lamorne Morris]] as Wilfred Wigans\n* [[Talulah Riley]] as Gina Garrison\n* Alex Hernandez as Marcus Tibbs\n* [[J\u00f3hannes Haukur J\u00f3hannesson]] as Nick Baris\n* Tamer Burjaq as  Mombasa Gunman\n* Siddharth Dhananjay as Eric\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\nIn March 2012, it was announced that [[Columbia Pictures]] had acquired the film rights to the [[Valiant Comics]] character [[Bloodshot (comics)|Bloodshot]], which would be produced by [[Original Film]] and [[Valiant Entertainment]]. [[Jeff Wadlow]] was hired to write the screenplay.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Todd|title=Columbia Bags Rights to Bloodshot, the Valiant Comics Character|url=https://www.thewrap.com/columbia-bags-rights-bloodshot-valiant-comics-character-35874/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=TheWrap|date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> In April 2015, [[Sony Pictures]], Original Film and Valiant announced a five-picture deal to bring Valiant Comics' superheroes to the big screen, including Bloodshot. [[Chad Stahelski]] and [[David Leitch (director)|David Leitch]] were hired to direct the film, from a screenplay by Wadlow and [[Eric Heisserer]].<ref name=\"Apr2015THR\">{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title='Bloodshot,' 'Harbinger' Comics to Get Film Treatment From Sony, Valiant Entertainment (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodshot-harbinger-comics-get-film-790433|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 21, 2015|language=en}}</ref> Stahelski and Leitch eventually passed on the project. In March 2017, Dave Wilson was announced as the director of the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnston|first1=Rich|title=Dave Wilson Is The Director Of The Bloodshot Movie For Sony And Valiant Entertainment (UPDATE \u2013 Examples Of Previous Work)|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/03/05/david-wilson-director-bloodshot-movie-sony-valiant-entertainment/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=Bleeding Cool|date=March 5, 2017}}</ref> Screenwriter [[Adam Cozad]] later contributed to the script.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-2-lands-legend-tarzan-writer-986284|title='Suicide Squad 2' Lands 'Legend of Tarzan' Writer (Exclusive)|date=March 15, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn July 2017, it was reported that [[Jared Leto]] was in early negotiations to star in the film as Bloodshot,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title=Jared Leto In Talks For \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 At Sony|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/jared-leto-bloodshot-sony-1202112262/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 25, 2017}}</ref> but in March 2018, it was announced that [[Vin Diesel]] would portray the main character.<ref name=\"DieselCast\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike, Jr|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=Vin Diesel Back In Action With Sony\u2019s \u2018Bloodshot\u2019, Valiant Comic Adaptation With Dave Wilson Directing|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-movie-sony-comic-book-dave-wilson-eric-heisserer-1202320751/|accessdate=March 9, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> By May, additional cast members were announced, with [[Sam Heughan]], [[Michael Sheen]], and [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]].<ref name=\"HeughanGonzalezSheenCast\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike, Jr|title=\u2018Outlander\u2019s Sam Heughan Joins Vin Diesel In Sony\u2019s \u2018Bloodshot\u2019; Eiza Gonzalez, Michael Sheen Also Aboard|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/sam-heughan-vin-diesel-sony-bloodshot-outlander-1202397024/|accessdate=May 24, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 23, 2018}}</ref> In June of the same year, [[Talulah Riley]] and Alex Hernandez were cast in the film to play the titular characters' wife named Gina, and member of a scientist team named Tibbs, respectively.<ref name=\"RileyHernandezCast\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title=Talulah Riley and Alex Hernandez in Talks to Join Vin Diesel in 'Bloodshot' |url=https://www.thewrap.com/talulah-riley-alex-hernandez-vin-diesel-bloodshot/ |accessdate=June 14, 2018 |work=TheWrap |date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Later, [[Toby Kebbell]] and Johannes Haukur Johannesson were both cast in villainous roles, with the former playing Axe.<ref name=\"KebbellCast\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title=Toby Kebbell Joins Cast of Vin Diesel's 'Bloodshot' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/toby-kebbell-vin-diesel-bloodshot/ |accessdate=June 27, 2018 |work=TheWrap |date=June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"JohannessonCast\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title='Game of Thrones' Actor Joins Vin Diesel's 'Bloodshot' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/johannes-haukur-johannesson-vin-diesel-bloodshot-game-of-thrones/ |accessdate=July 1, 2018 |work=TheWrap |date=June 29, 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Lamorne Morris]] was hired to play a young scientist named Wilfred Wigans.<ref name=\"MorrisCast\">{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Lamorne Morris Loads Up Sony\u2019s Vin Diesel Movie \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/vin-diesel-bloodshot-movie-casts-lamorne-morris-new-girl-actor-1202438518/ |accessdate=August 3, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> In the same month, it was reported that [[Guy Pearce]] was in talks to replace Sheen, who had to exit the movie due to scheduling and family conflicts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=N'Duka |first1=Amanda  |title=Guy Pearce In Talks To Take Over Michael Sheen\u2019s Role In Sony\u2019s \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 Movie |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/guy-pearce-michael-sheen-sony-bloodshot-1202441902/ |accessdate=August 7, 2018 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography began on August 6, 2018 in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], and in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]], with some filming taking place in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]] in that same month.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marc |first1=Christopher |title=Vin Diesel's 'Bloodshot' Begins Filming August 6th In Europe and South Africa \u2013 GWW |url=https://thegww.com/vin-diesels-bloodshot-begins-filming-august-6th-in-europe-and-south-africa/ |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |work=GWW |date=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marc|first1=Christopher|title=UPDATE: 'Bloodshot' Movie Now Eyeing Summer Shoot In Prague \u2013 Omega Underground|url=https://omegaunderground.com/2018/04/11/update-bloodshot-movie-now-eyeing-summer-shoot-in-prague/|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=omegaunderground.com|date=April 12, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Filming officially wrapped on October 25, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mueller|first1=Matthew|title=Vin Diesel Shares New Video To Celebrate Wrapping 'Bloodshot'|url=https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/10/26/vin-diesel-wrapping-bloodshot-video/|accessdate=October 28, 2018|work=Comicbook.com|date=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\nThe first trailer for ''Bloodshot'' was released on October 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/trailers/a29525531/bloodshot-trailer-vin-diesel/|title=First trailer for Vin Diesel's comic book movie Bloodshot is coming tomorrow|last=Davies|first=Megan|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref> It features [[Johnny Cash]]'s cover of the song \"[[Memories Are Made of This]]\".\n\n== Release ==\n''Bloodshot'' was released in the United States on March 13, 2020, by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]], after previously being scheduled to release on February 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Spencer |title=Sony Sets Release Dates for Bloodshot, Little Women, and More |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/958771-sony-sets-release-dates-for-bloodshot-little-women-and-more |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |work=ComingSoon.net |date=July 18, 2018}}</ref> It also opened in the UK, Ireland and India on the same day.<ref name=\"Filmoria.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/bloodshot-will-open-at-cinemas-across-uk-and-ireland-march-13th/|title=BLOODSHOT will open at cinemas across UK and Ireland March 13th|publisher=Filmoria.co.uk|date= |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFive days after the release, Sony confirmed that the film will be released digitally on March 24, 2020, due to [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-coronavirus-available-in-home-1202887011/|title=\u2018Bloodshot\u2019 Available In Homes & Mobile On March 24: Coronavirus|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Over its first three days of home release, the film was the most watched on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime]] and fourth-most on [[iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/farewell-box-office-premium-vod-charts-bloodshot-onward-birds-of-prey-1202220714/ |title=\u2018Farewell, Box Office: This Was the Week That Premium VOD Charts Took Flight\n|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Tom|last= Brueggemann |date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Bloodshot'' grossed $10 million in the United States and Canada, and $20.1 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $30.1 million, against a production budget of $45 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[The Hunt (2020 film)|The Hunt]]'' and ''[[I Still Believe (film)|I Still Believe]]'', and was projected to gross around $10 million from 2,861 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=WrapProj>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thewrap.com/i-still-believe-bloodshot-hunt-box-office/ |title= \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Expected to Top \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 and \u2018The Hunt\u2019 at Weekend Box Office |website=[[TheWrap]]|author=Jeremy Fuster|accessdate=March 10, 2020|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The film made $3.8 million on its first day, including $1.2 million from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $9.3 million, finishing third. The weekend was also noteworthy for being the lowest combined-grossing since October 1998, with all films totaling just $55.3 million, in large part from societal restrictions and regulations due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]].<ref name=opening>{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/ |title= Vin Diesel Pic \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 Leads Thursday Previews With $1.2M As Cinemas Contend With Coronavirus Outbreak |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 13, 2020|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> In the film's second weekend, due to the mass theater closures around the country, made $52,000 from 79 locations, mostly [[drive-in theater|drive-ins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-drive-in-movie-theaters-exhibition-shutdown-onward-1202890329/ |title=Drive-Ins Continue To Post Best Ticket Sales In Weekend Box Office Wiped Out By Theater Closures |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 23, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 30% based on 142 reviews, with an average rating of 4.59/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Bloodshot'' gives Vin Diesel a solid opportunity to indulge in old-school action that should satisfy fans, even if the end result is disappointingly mediocre.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Bloodshot (2020)|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bloodshot_2020/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 44 out of 100, based on 34 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Bloodshot Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/bloodshot |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received  an average 3 out of 5 stars, with 45% saying they would definitely recommend it.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 2 out of 4 stars, calling it ambitious but \"intermittently entertaining\" and \"frantically overcooked, bursting with headache-inducing, rapid-cut action sequences\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2020/3/12/21174371/bloodshot-review-vin-diesel-movie-superhero-film|title=\u2018Bloodshot\u2019: Tech makes Vin Diesel a new man doing the same old stuff|last=Roeper|first=Richard|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Future ==\nIntended to launch a new [[Shared universe|shared cinematic universe]] of Valiant Comics superheroes, ''Bloodshot'' was originally planned to be followed by four movies: a sequel, two films based on the comic book series ''[[Harbinger (comic book)|Harbinger]]'', and a culmination in a [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] titled ''Harbinger Wars''.<ref name=\"Apr2015THR\"/> Initially scheduled to be the first installment in the franchise, development of ''Harbinger'' was delayed in favor of releasing ''Bloodshot'' first.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Umberto|title=Sony Moves Up Plans for 'Harbinger' as 1st Movie in Valiant Comics Cinematic Universe (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/valiant-comics-harbinger-bloodshot-sony-cinematic-universe/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=TheWrap|date=September 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Apr2015THR /> In September 2019, it was announced that ''Harbinger'' would be distributed by [[Paramount Pictures]], possibly canceling any shared universe plans with ''Bloodshot''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/paramount-picks-up-comic-book-movie-harbinger-sony-1238972|title=Paramount Picks Up Comic Book Movie 'Harbinger' From Sony (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, it was announced that a film centered around the superhero [[Faith Herbert|Faith]] was also in development, with a script from Maria Melnik.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/faith-plus-sized-female-superhero-sony-pictures-valiant-comics-maria-melnik-1202419224/ |title=Hollywood\u2019s First Plus-Size Superhero? Sony Sets Maria Melnik To Script Pic On Valiant Comics\u2019 \u2018Faith\u2019 |date=June 28, 2018 |first=Mike, Jr |last=Fleming |website=Deadline Hollywod}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2020, an updated film version of ''[[Ninjak vs. the Valiant Universe]]'', featuring [[Jason David Frank]] as Bloodshot, was released on [[YouTube]] page as promotion for ''Bloodshot''.<ref name=\"film\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DA8YHf-zXsk|title=NINJAK VS THE VALIANT UNIVERSE - From Valiant Entertainment and Bat In the Sun Productions|website=[[YouTube]]|last=Comics|first=Valiant|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.sonypictures.com/movies/bloodshot}}\n* {{IMDb title|1634106}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|Bloodshot_2020}}\n*{{Movie Review By Er. Bed Kaushik|https://review.bed.com.np/2020/04/bloodshotmovie.html}}\n{{Valiant}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:2020s superhero films]]\n[[Category:2020s vigilante films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American superhero films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about amnesia]]\n[[Category:Films based on American comics]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Neal H. Moritz]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Films set in Budapest]]\n[[Category:Films set in Campania]]\n[[Category:Films set in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Budapest]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Live-action films based on comics]]\n[[Category:Original Film films]]\n[[Category:One Race Films films]]\n[[Category:2020 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 film directed by David S. F. Wilson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Bloodshot\n| image          = File:Bloodshot - official film poster.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = David S. F. Wilson\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Neal H. Moritz]]\n* Toby Jaffe\n* Dinesh Shamdasani\n* [[Vin Diesel]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jeff Wadlow]]\n* [[Eric Heisserer]]\n}}\n| story          = Jeff Wadlow\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Bloodshot (comics)|Bloodshot]]|[[Kevin VanHook]]|[[Don Perlin]]|[[Bob Layton]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Vin Diesel]]\n* [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n* [[Sam Heughan]]\n* [[Toby Kebbell]]\n* [[Guy Pearce]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Steve Jablonsky]]\n| cinematography = Jacques Jouffret\n| editing        = Jim May\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Bona Film Group]]\n* [[Cross Creek Pictures]]\n* Annabell Pictures\n* The Hideaway Entertainment\n* [[Original Film]]\n* [[One Race Films]]\n* [[Valiant Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|3|13|United States}}\n| runtime        = 109 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $45\nmillion<ref name=BOM/>\n| gross          = $29.2 million<ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Bloodshot-(2020)#tab=summary |title=Bloodshot (2020) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl235374081/?ref_=bo_hm_rs |title=Bloodshot (2020) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Bloodshot''''' is a 2020 American [[superhero film]] based on the [[Valiant Comics]] character [[Bloodshot (comics)|of the same name]]. It is intended to be the first installment in a series of films set within a Valiant Comics [[Shared universe|shared cinematic universe]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/valiant-entertainment-is-jumping-from-comics-to-movies-and-tv-2019-9 |title=How Valiant Entertainment is jumping from comics to movies and TV |author=Travis Clark |date=September 18, 2019 |website=Business Insider}}</ref> Directed by David S. F. Wilson (in his feature directorial debut) from a screenplay by [[Jeff Wadlow]] and [[Eric Heisserer]] and a story by Wadlow,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://findawriter.wgaeast.org/project/1156287/bloodshot/ |title=Bloodshot |website=WGA Directory}}</ref> the film stars [[Vin Diesel]], [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Sam Heughan]], [[Toby Kebbell]], and [[Guy Pearce]]. It follows a Marine who was killed in action, only to be brought back to life with superpowers by an organization that wants to use him as a weapon.\n\nDevelopment of a Bloodshot film began in 2012, with [[Jared Leto]] originally in talks to star in July 2017. In March 2018, Diesel was hired to portray the title role, and the rest of the cast joined over the following months. Filming commenced in South Africa in August 2018, lasting through October.\n\n''Bloodshot'' was theatrically released in the United States on March 13, 2020, by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]. The film received mixed reviews from critics and has grossed $29 million worldwide. Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] closing theaters across the globe, Sony made the film available digitally on-demand less than two weeks after it was released theatrically.\n\n==Plot==\nAfter leading a successful rescue operation in [[Mombasa]], U.S. Airman Ray Garrison and his wife Gina travel for a holiday at an Italian beachside town in the [[Amalfi Coast]]. However, they are kidnapped by a group of mercenaries led by Martin Axe, who demands to know the source of the Mombasa hostage operation. Since Ray is not privy to this information, Axe kills him and Gina.\n\nRay is later resurrected by Rising Spirit Tech, a company that specializes in developing cybernetic enhancements for disabled US military personnel. The company's CEO, Dr. Emil Harting, tells Ray that he is the first successful candidate that they have resurrected using a [[nanorobotics|special nanite technology]]. Ray is also introduced to Dr Harting's other patients including former [[United States Navy|US Navy]] diver \"KT\", whom he strikes a friendship with, and former soldiers Jimmy Dalton and Marcus Tibbs, with whom he gets on poorly.\n\nAfter experiencing \"flashbacks\" of Gina and Axe, Ray escapes Rising Spirit's laboratory in [[Kuala Lumpur]] and pursues Axe, seeking to avenge Gina's death. Using the nanites to hack into computer databases, Ray tracks down Axe to [[Budapest]]. After trapping his convoy in a tunnel, Ray kills Axe's bodyguards before executing the mercenary. He is later recovered by KT, Dalton and Tibbs, who bring him back to Rising Spirit for reprogramming. In truth, Harting created false memories of Gina's death as part of a plot to eliminate rivals in Rising Spirit.\n\nAfter his memories are wiped and reprogrammed, Ray is sent to kill Nick Baris in [[East Sussex]], \"remembering\" him to be Gina's killer. Though Ray manages to kill Baris and his bodyguards, Baris has forced computer programmer Wilfred Wigans to build an [[electromagnetic pulse|EMP bomb]], which is ignited after Baris' death, incapacitating Ray and severing communications with Rising Spirit. After \"resurrecting\" Ray, Wigans reveals that Rising Spirit planted false memories to turn him into a killing machine. Ray also discovers Gina is alive but had left him five years ago and started a family in [[Westminster]].\n\nGrowing disillusioned with Harting's exploitation of Ray, KT seeks Wigans' help in taking him down. Meanwhile, Ray is recaptured by Dalton and Tibbs following a pursuit. He is brought back to Rising Spirit's laboratory for reprogramming, but escapes with the help of KT and Wigans, who sabotage the reprogramming process and Rising Spirit's computers. Breaking free, Ray fights Dalton and Tibbs on top of an elevator. Dalton willingly lets Tibbs fall to his death before continuing the fight until Ray punches him down the elevator shaft, killing him. Ray confronts Harting, who manages to drain the nanites, but is killed when the second grenade he shoots at Ray is dismantled by the nanites and dropped directly at his feet. Ray is later rebuilt by Wigans and KT, and the three then leave in search of a new life.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vin Diesel]] as [[Bloodshot (comics)|Ray Garrison / Bloodshot]]\n* [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]] as KT\n* [[Sam Heughan]] as Jimmy Dalton\n* [[Toby Kebbell]] as Martin Axe\n* [[Guy Pearce]] as Dr. Emil Harting\n* [[Lamorne Morris]] as Wilfred Wigans\n* [[Talulah Riley]] as Gina Garrison\n* Alex Hernandez as Marcus Tibbs\n* [[J\u00f3hannes Haukur J\u00f3hannesson]] as Nick Baris\n* Tamer Burjaq as  Mombasa Gunman\n* Siddharth Dhananjay as Eric\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\nIn March 2012, it was announced that [[Columbia Pictures]] had acquired the film rights to the [[Valiant Comics]] character [[Bloodshot (comics)|Bloodshot]], which would be produced by [[Original Film]] and [[Valiant Entertainment]]. [[Jeff Wadlow]] was hired to write the screenplay.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Todd|title=Columbia Bags Rights to Bloodshot, the Valiant Comics Character|url=https://www.thewrap.com/columbia-bags-rights-bloodshot-valiant-comics-character-35874/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=TheWrap|date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> In April 2015, [[Sony Pictures]], Original Film and Valiant announced a five-picture deal to bring Valiant Comics' superheroes to the big screen, including Bloodshot. [[Chad Stahelski]] and [[David Leitch (director)|David Leitch]] were hired to direct the film, from a screenplay by Wadlow and [[Eric Heisserer]].<ref name=\"Apr2015THR\">{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title='Bloodshot,' 'Harbinger' Comics to Get Film Treatment From Sony, Valiant Entertainment (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/bloodshot-harbinger-comics-get-film-790433|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 21, 2015|language=en}}</ref> Stahelski and Leitch eventually passed on the project. In March 2017, Dave Wilson was announced as the director of the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnston|first1=Rich|title=Dave Wilson Is The Director Of The Bloodshot Movie For Sony And Valiant Entertainment (UPDATE \u2013 Examples Of Previous Work)|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/03/05/david-wilson-director-bloodshot-movie-sony-valiant-entertainment/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=Bleeding Cool|date=March 5, 2017}}</ref> Screenwriter [[Adam Cozad]] later contributed to the script.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/suicide-squad-2-lands-legend-tarzan-writer-986284|title='Suicide Squad 2' Lands 'Legend of Tarzan' Writer (Exclusive)|date=March 15, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn July 2017, it was reported that [[Jared Leto]] was in early negotiations to star in the film as Bloodshot,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title=Jared Leto In Talks For \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 At Sony|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/jared-leto-bloodshot-sony-1202112262/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 25, 2017}}</ref> but in March 2018, it was announced that [[Vin Diesel]] would portray the main character.<ref name=\"DieselCast\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike, Jr|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=Vin Diesel Back In Action With Sony\u2019s \u2018Bloodshot\u2019, Valiant Comic Adaptation With Dave Wilson Directing|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-movie-sony-comic-book-dave-wilson-eric-heisserer-1202320751/|accessdate=March 9, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> By May, additional cast members were announced, with [[Sam Heughan]], [[Michael Sheen]], and [[Eiza Gonz\u00e1lez]].<ref name=\"HeughanGonzalezSheenCast\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike, Jr|title=\u2018Outlander\u2019s Sam Heughan Joins Vin Diesel In Sony\u2019s \u2018Bloodshot\u2019; Eiza Gonzalez, Michael Sheen Also Aboard|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/sam-heughan-vin-diesel-sony-bloodshot-outlander-1202397024/|accessdate=May 24, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 23, 2018}}</ref> In June of the same year, [[Talulah Riley]] and Alex Hernandez were cast in the film to play the titular characters' wife named Gina, and member of a scientist team named Tibbs, respectively.<ref name=\"RileyHernandezCast\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title=Talulah Riley and Alex Hernandez in Talks to Join Vin Diesel in 'Bloodshot' |url=https://www.thewrap.com/talulah-riley-alex-hernandez-vin-diesel-bloodshot/ |accessdate=June 14, 2018 |work=TheWrap |date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Later, [[Toby Kebbell]] and Johannes Haukur Johannesson were both cast in villainous roles, with the former playing Axe.<ref name=\"KebbellCast\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title=Toby Kebbell Joins Cast of Vin Diesel's 'Bloodshot' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/toby-kebbell-vin-diesel-bloodshot/ |accessdate=June 27, 2018 |work=TheWrap |date=June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"JohannessonCast\">{{cite news |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Umberto |title='Game of Thrones' Actor Joins Vin Diesel's 'Bloodshot' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/johannes-haukur-johannesson-vin-diesel-bloodshot-game-of-thrones/ |accessdate=July 1, 2018 |work=TheWrap |date=June 29, 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Lamorne Morris]] was hired to play a young scientist named Wilfred Wigans.<ref name=\"MorrisCast\">{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Lamorne Morris Loads Up Sony\u2019s Vin Diesel Movie \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/vin-diesel-bloodshot-movie-casts-lamorne-morris-new-girl-actor-1202438518/ |accessdate=August 3, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> In the same month, it was reported that [[Guy Pearce]] was in talks to replace Sheen, who had to exit the movie due to scheduling and family conflicts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=N'Duka |first1=Amanda  |title=Guy Pearce In Talks To Take Over Michael Sheen\u2019s Role In Sony\u2019s \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 Movie |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/guy-pearce-michael-sheen-sony-bloodshot-1202441902/ |accessdate=August 7, 2018 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nPrincipal photography began on August 6, 2018 in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], and in [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]], with some filming taking place in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]] in that same month.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marc |first1=Christopher |title=Vin Diesel's 'Bloodshot' Begins Filming August 6th In Europe and South Africa \u2013 GWW |url=https://thegww.com/vin-diesels-bloodshot-begins-filming-august-6th-in-europe-and-south-africa/ |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |work=GWW |date=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marc|first1=Christopher|title=UPDATE: 'Bloodshot' Movie Now Eyeing Summer Shoot In Prague \u2013 Omega Underground|url=https://omegaunderground.com/2018/04/11/update-bloodshot-movie-now-eyeing-summer-shoot-in-prague/|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=omegaunderground.com|date=April 12, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Filming officially wrapped on October 25, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mueller|first1=Matthew|title=Vin Diesel Shares New Video To Celebrate Wrapping 'Bloodshot'|url=https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/10/26/vin-diesel-wrapping-bloodshot-video/|accessdate=October 28, 2018|work=Comicbook.com|date=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\nThe first trailer for ''Bloodshot'' was released on October 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/trailers/a29525531/bloodshot-trailer-vin-diesel/|title=First trailer for Vin Diesel's comic book movie Bloodshot is coming tomorrow|last=Davies|first=Megan|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref> It features [[Johnny Cash]]'s cover of the song \"[[Memories Are Made of This]]\".\n\n== Release ==\n''Bloodshot'' was released in the United States on March 13, 2020, by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]], after previously being scheduled to release on February 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Spencer |title=Sony Sets Release Dates for Bloodshot, Little Women, and More |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/958771-sony-sets-release-dates-for-bloodshot-little-women-and-more |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |work=ComingSoon.net |date=July 18, 2018}}</ref> It also opened in the UK, Ireland and India on the same day.<ref name=\"Filmoria.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/bloodshot-will-open-at-cinemas-across-uk-and-ireland-march-13th/|title=BLOODSHOT will open at cinemas across UK and Ireland March 13th|publisher=Filmoria.co.uk|date= |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFive days after the release, Sony confirmed that the film will be released digitally on March 24, 2020, due to [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-coronavirus-available-in-home-1202887011/|title=\u2018Bloodshot\u2019 Available In Homes & Mobile On March 24: Coronavirus|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Over its first three days of home release, the film was the most watched on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime]] and fourth-most on [[iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/farewell-box-office-premium-vod-charts-bloodshot-onward-birds-of-prey-1202220714/ |title=\u2018Farewell, Box Office: This Was the Week That Premium VOD Charts Took Flight\n|website=[[IndieWire]]|first=Tom|last= Brueggemann |date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Bloodshot'' grossed $10 million in the United States and Canada, and $20.1 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $30.1 million, against a production budget of $45 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[The Hunt (2020 film)|The Hunt]]'' and ''[[I Still Believe (film)|I Still Believe]]'', and was projected to gross around $10 million from 2,861 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=WrapProj>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thewrap.com/i-still-believe-bloodshot-hunt-box-office/ |title= \u2018I Still Believe\u2019 Expected to Top \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 and \u2018The Hunt\u2019 at Weekend Box Office |website=[[TheWrap]]|author=Jeremy Fuster|accessdate=March 10, 2020|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The film made $3.8 million on its first day, including $1.2 million from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $9.3 million, finishing third. The weekend was also noteworthy for being the lowest combined-grossing since October 1998, with all films totaling just $55.3 million, in large part from societal restrictions and regulations due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]].<ref name=opening>{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/ |title= Vin Diesel Pic \u2018Bloodshot\u2019 Leads Thursday Previews With $1.2M As Cinemas Contend With Coronavirus Outbreak |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 13, 2020|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> In the film's second weekend, due to the mass theater closures around the country, made $52,000 from 79 locations, mostly [[drive-in theater|drive-ins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-drive-in-movie-theaters-exhibition-shutdown-onward-1202890329/ |title=Drive-Ins Continue To Post Best Ticket Sales In Weekend Box Office Wiped Out By Theater Closures |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=March 23, 2020 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 30% based on 142 reviews, with an average rating of 4.59/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Bloodshot'' gives Vin Diesel a solid opportunity to indulge in old-school action that should satisfy fans, even if the end result is disappointingly mediocre.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Bloodshot (2020)|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bloodshot_2020/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 44 out of 100, based on 34 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Bloodshot Reviews |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/bloodshot |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, and [[PostTrak]] reported it received  an average 3 out of 5 stars, with 45% saying they would definitely recommend it.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 2 out of 4 stars, calling it ambitious but \"intermittently entertaining\" and \"frantically overcooked, bursting with headache-inducing, rapid-cut action sequences\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2020/3/12/21174371/bloodshot-review-vin-diesel-movie-superhero-film|title=\u2018Bloodshot\u2019: Tech makes Vin Diesel a new man doing the same old stuff|last=Roeper|first=Richard|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Future ==\nIntended to launch a new [[Shared universe|shared cinematic universe]] of Valiant Comics superheroes, ''Bloodshot'' was originally planned to be followed by four movies: a sequel, two films based on the comic book series ''[[Harbinger (comic book)|Harbinger]]'', and a culmination in a [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] titled ''Harbinger Wars''.<ref name=\"Apr2015THR\"/> Initially scheduled to be the first installment in the franchise, development of ''Harbinger'' was delayed in favor of releasing ''Bloodshot'' first.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Umberto|title=Sony Moves Up Plans for 'Harbinger' as 1st Movie in Valiant Comics Cinematic Universe (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/valiant-comics-harbinger-bloodshot-sony-cinematic-universe/|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=TheWrap|date=September 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Apr2015THR /> In September 2019, it was announced that ''Harbinger'' would be distributed by [[Paramount Pictures]], possibly canceling any shared universe plans with ''Bloodshot''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/paramount-picks-up-comic-book-movie-harbinger-sony-1238972|title=Paramount Picks Up Comic Book Movie 'Harbinger' From Sony (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, it was announced that a film centered around the superhero [[Faith Herbert|Faith]] was also in development, with a script from Maria Melnik.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/faith-plus-sized-female-superhero-sony-pictures-valiant-comics-maria-melnik-1202419224/ |title=Hollywood\u2019s First Plus-Size Superhero? Sony Sets Maria Melnik To Script Pic On Valiant Comics\u2019 \u2018Faith\u2019 |date=June 28, 2018 |first=Mike, Jr |last=Fleming |website=Deadline Hollywod}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2020, an updated film version of ''[[Ninjak vs. the Valiant Universe]]'', featuring [[Jason David Frank]] as Bloodshot, was released on [[YouTube]] page as promotion for ''Bloodshot''.<ref name=\"film\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DA8YHf-zXsk|title=NINJAK VS THE VALIANT UNIVERSE - From Valiant Entertainment and Bat In the Sun Productions|website=[[YouTube]]|last=Comics|first=Valiant|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.sonypictures.com/movies/bloodshot}}\n* {{IMDb title|1634106}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|Bloodshot_2020}}\n*{{https://review.bed.com.np/2020/04/bloodshotmovie.html}}\n{{Valiant}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:2020s superhero films]]\n[[Category:2020s vigilante films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American superhero films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about amnesia]]\n[[Category:Films based on American comics]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Neal H. Moritz]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Films set in Budapest]]\n[[Category:Films set in Campania]]\n[[Category:Films set in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Budapest]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Live-action films based on comics]]\n[[Category:Original Film films]]\n[[Category:One Race Films films]]\n[[Category:2020 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "BedKaushik", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloodshot_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Clara (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 romantic science fiction film directed by Akash Sherman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Clara\n| image          = Clara poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = Akash Sherman\n| producer       = Ari Lantos\n| writer         = \n{{Plainlist|\n*Akash Sherman\n*James Ewasiuk\n}}\n| starring       = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Patrick J. Adams]]\n*[[Troian Bellisario]]\n}}\n| music          = Jonathan Kawchuk\n| cinematography = Nick Haight\n| editing        = Matt Lyon\n| production companies = Serendipity Point Films ''in association with'' Distant Horizon\n| distributor    = D Films\n| released       = {{film date|2018|09|10|[[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = Canada, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Clara''''' is a 2018 Canadian-British [[science fiction film]] and the second feature film directed by Akash Sherman. The film stars husband and wife actors [[Patrick J. Adams]] and [[Troian Bellisario]], playing astrophysicist Isaac and itinerant artist Clara, who become close while searching for signs of intelligent life in the universe. The film is grounded in recent technological and theoretical advances, and attracted the attention of astronomers. The film received mixed reviews from critics, and out of a handful of nominations from various bodies, won an award from the [[Austin Film Festival]], \n\n==Plot==\nDr. Isaac Bruno holds a postdoctoral research fellowship in astrophysics at (fictional) Ontario University, in [[Toronto]]. His goal of finding signs of intelligent life in the universe has become an obsession, linked to an unspecified trauma in his personal life two years earlier. He has become increasingly antagonistic towards his students and has taken to misappropriating time on ground-based telescopes in Chile, intended for a colleague's research. His department head suspends him, denying him any access to the school's research facilities.\n\nThe [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] orbiting telescope is launched, providing enormous amounts of data that is shared with the world, in a community effort to analyze and find possible life on [[exoplanet]]s. Isaac posts flyers looking for an unpaid research assistant, offering nothing but room and board. His only response is from Clara, an uneducated artist who has lived a [[Bohemianism|Bohemian lifestyle]]. Clara has her own secrets, seen taking some type of medicine for an unspecified issue.\n\nIsaac focuses on results from [[Red dwarf|M dwarf]] stars, believing it to be a niche that no one else will bother with. When Clara finds a promising exoplanet, Isaac sneaks into the university in the night and lies to the telescope operators in Chile, claiming to have permission from his friend Charlie, to get more data on the planet.\n\nCharlie is furious, but also intrigued by the data results. He advises Isaac to contact Rebecca, Isaac's ex-wife, who holds an endowed chair at [[California Institute of Technology|Caltech]]. Clara convinces Isaac to contact Rebecca, despite his reluctance. The upheaval in their lives is finally revealed, when Rebecca tells Isaac that finding life will not bring back their dead baby son. She gets him some time on the [[W. M. Keck Observatory|Keck]] telescope. This results in proving that they have found a [[Planetary habitability|habitable planet candidate]].\n\nClara is falling in love with Isaac, but he has become jaded about love or anything else that can not be scientifically proven. She kisses him, then abruptly backs off when he starts to respond. When Charlie's wife has a baby, Isaac pontificates on how a minuscule change took his own son, and could equally change the entire universe. Clara reminds him that those same minuscule changes did result in his son existing at all. This leads to them finally becoming a couple. \n\nWhen they learn that someone else discovered \u201ctheir\u201d planet a week before them, Isaac becomes despondent. He soon decides to focus on finding direct evidence of life, rather than just a potentially habitable planet. In his obsession, he is blind to Clara's declining health, until Charlie chastises him. Isaac tells Clara it is time for him to stop his search, but she makes him ignore the data and focus on his inner connection to the universe. He is surprised when it works, but rejects it and her. She grabs her bag to leave - and collapses.\n\nAt the hospital, it is revealed that Clara has an autoimmune disease that is causing the complete breakdown of every organ and muscle in her body. The doctors are shocked that she can even walk or talk, and confirm she will soon be dead. Isaac stays at her bedside for her last few days. Moments before she dies, she tells him he is going to \u201csee it\u201d.\n\nA fresh batch of TESS data is released, and Isaac does \u201csee it\u201d - proof of a seemingly artificial object in coincident orbit with an exoplanet. He takes his findings to Charlie, who introduces him to Dr. Rickman, head of the TESS project. Two years later, at a press conference at the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory|JPL]], Dr. Rickman, Rebecca and Charlie explain that the data gathered now conclusively proves the existence of the artificial object, orbiting a star 200 light years distant, in turn proving the existence of intelligent alien life. Isaac is not in his assigned seat on the panel, choosing instead to spend time reminiscing about Clara.\n\nA few months later, Rebecca summons Isaac to the [[Search for extraterrestrial intelligence|SETI]] laboratory. She reveals that the aliens have sent a message&mdash;\u201cIsaac Bruno\u201d. He is present when the next message arrives &ndash; an audio file of a [[Bob Dylan]] song that he and Clara often listened to together. The film ends with Isaac smiling through his tears.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Patrick J. Adams]] as Dr. Isaac Bruno \n* [[Troian Bellisario]] as Clara\n* [[Ennis Esmer]] as Dr. Charlie Durant \n* [[Kristen Hager]] as Dr. Rebecca Jenkins \n* [[R. H. Thomson]] as Dr. Rickman\n* [[Jennifer Dale]] as Astrophysics Department Head\n\n==Themes and genre==\nA story about \"space and love\",<ref name=\"Slotek\">{{cite web |last1=Slotek |first1=Jim (interviewer) |title=Original-Cin Review/Q&A: Clara Filmmaker Shoots for the Stars (and Mostly Reaches \u2018Em, Too) |url=https://www.original-cin.ca/posts/2018/11/27/original-cin-reviewqampa-clara-filmmaker-shoots-for-the-stars-and-mostly-reaches-em-too |website=Original-Cin.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Akash Sherman titled the film ''Clara'' because the word means \"clear\" and \"bright,\" like a star: \"it was about this search for life among the stars.\"<ref name=\"Billings\">{{cite journal |last1=Billings |first1=Lee (interviewer) |title=''Clara'' Is a Story of Exoplanets, Existential Longing\u2014and Real Science |journal=[[Scientific American]] |date=11 October 2018 |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/clara-is-a-story-of-exoplanets-existential-longing-mdash-and-real-science1/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nSherman calls the film a \"[[high concept]]\" [[science fiction]] drama.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> He does not consider it a [[romantic film|romance]], but anticipated it would be marketed that way \"because the lead actors are married in real life\"; it is a love story to the extent that there is \"a binding bond between two characters\" who are \"just two people connecting for a bit.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Jim Slotek disagrees: \"Sherman's objections notwithstanding, ''Clara'' is a romance, albeit an interrupted one \u2014 kind of what you'd get if you crossed Carl Sagan's ''Contact'' with Erich Segal's ''Love Story.''\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nAt age 18, Sherman competed in the CineCoup Film Accelerator at the [[Banff World Media Festival]], where he won second place and attracted the attention of producer Ari Lantos.<ref name=\"Malyk\">{{cite journal |last1=Malyk |first1=Lauren |title=TIFF \u201918: The winning formula behind Akash Sherman\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=10 September 2018 |url=https://playbackonline.ca/2018/09/10/clara-a-sci-fi-stepping-stone/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman studied at [[Ryerson University]]'s film school for one year, where one day, at 19, he became determined to write a story, shutting himself in his dormitory room for seven hours.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> \n\n===Writing and development===\nFriends Sherman made at Ryerson worked with him on his debut, ''The Rocket List'', \"made on no budget ... on a four-day road trip with a camera,\"<ref name=\"Malyk\" /> as well as on ''Clara''.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Together with James Ewasiuk, a \"close collaborator\" who co-wrote ''The Rocket List'' with him, Sherman did four months of research on \"the Kepler telescope and transits and things like that.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Two years after they had met in Banff, Sherman ran into Lantos while pitching the draft script to Serendipity Point Films, from whom he received an option agreement the next day.<ref name=\"Malyk\" />\n\nBoth romantic leads also contributed ideas. Patrick Adams was involved with the project from an early stage, giving feedback to Sherman on his script, on character in particular, which the director began revising in earnest at age 20 and finished two years later.<ref name=\"Knight\" /> Troian Bellisario provided \"a similar depth for her character,\" and suggested a different ending for the film, a note which Sherman accepted: \"I had a different ending in mind, which I don't want to share because it's not as good.\"<ref name=\"Knight\" /> It was Bellisario who brought up [[quantum entanglement]] for one of the earlier drafts.<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\nThe project relied on three scientific advisors, Canadian astrophysicists John Moores and Doug Welch,<ref name=\"Billings\" /> at [[York University|York]] and [[McMaster University|McMaster]] universities respectively, and Barth Netterfeld of the [[University of Toronto]].<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Sherman and producer Ari Santos sent out an e-mail to Toronto-area physics and astronomy departments asking for help. Welch responded because there was so much \"real science\" in Sherman's script.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> During [[preproduction]] Welch spent time with Sherman, Adams, and Bellisario, explaining such concepts as the [[Fermi paradox]] and the [[Drake equation]] in relation to the mechanics of astronomical observing, and later also also suggested some dialogue exchanges.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> Accoding to Sherman, almost everything was vetted by the three consultants. \"It's so vetted, in fact, that the climactic discovery in the movie... turned out to be an original idea\", later published by the [[American Astronomical Society]].<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Financing===\n''Clara'' was produced by Serendipity Point in association with [[London]]-based Distant Horizon, with the support of [[Telefilm Canada]], the Ontario Media Development Corporation (Ontario Creates), the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], and [[Bell Media]]'s [[The Movie Network|TMN]].<ref name=\"Malyk\" /><ref name=\"Pinto\">{{cite journal |last1=Pinto |first1=Jordan |title=Production begins on Serendipity Point\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=7 March 2017 |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2017/03/07/production-begins-on-serendipity-points-clara/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] took place in [[Toronto]] and surrounding areas during the month of March in 2017.<ref name=\"Pinto\" /> Leads Adams and Bellisario were married a little earlier,<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite news |last1=Knight |first1=Chris |title=Akash Sherman looks to the cosmos for Clara, his second feature film |url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/akash-sherman-looks-to-the-cosmos-for-clara-his-second-feature-film |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[The National Post]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and spent a large portion of their [[honeymoon]] working on the film.<ref name=\"Collider\">{{cite web |title=Clara: Patrick J. Adams, Ari Lantos, and Director Akash Sherman on Their Grounded Sci-Fi Film [Collider interview] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFHtf7vTBmg |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020 |format=video}}</ref> \n\n====Locations====\nLocations included Sherman's [[alma mater]] Ryerson and the [[Mississauga]] campus of the University of Toronto for several NASA scenes, because of their \"spectacular buildings\".<ref name=\"Davidson\">{{cite journal |last1=Davidson |first1=Sonya (interviewer) |title=CLARA searches for life and connection beyond our world |url=https://torontoguardian.com/2018/12/clara-film-akash-sherman/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=Toronto Guardian |date=7 December 2018}}</ref> There are also outdoor scenes shot near [[Sugar Beach]], while a shot of the exterior of the [[McLaughlin Planetarium]] in Toronto was not included in the final cut of the theatrical release.<ref name=\"Davidson\" />\n\n====Visual effects and scientific accuracy====\nThe detection method and the specialized telescopes depicted in ''Clara'' are not fictional. The [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] space telescope is a 2018 upgrade of the [[Kepler Telescope]] which was used to discover over 4000 [[exoplanets]] in the decade since 2009.<ref name=\"Shanahan\">{{cite web |last1=Shanahan |first1=Don |title=Clara Grounds Solemnity and Sweetness Into Complicated Love Within Science Fiction |url=https://25yearslatersite.com/2019/09/19/clara-grounds-solemnity-and-sweetness-into-complicated-love-within-science-fiction/ |website=25YearsLaterSite.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman started his filmmaking career as [[visual effects]] artist, and all such shots in the film were made by him rather than by his cinematographer, sourced from [[NASA]]: shots of planets transiting a sun come from the [[Solar Dynamics Observatory]]; shots of nebulae come from the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] : \"I really wanted to show space honestly and in a way that would look familiar to people working in the field.\"<ref name=\"Billings\" />\n\n===Music===\nComposer Jonathan Kawchuk wrote a \"soft score\", complimenting musical selections by [[Bob Dylan]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> Kawchuk converted sounds from NASA's [[Voyager spacecraft]] into a [[synthesizer]], sounds which were \"baked into a lot of the tracks.\"<ref name=\"Billings\" />\n\n==Marketing and related works==\nLantos said that ''Clara'' was aimed at teenagers and women in their twenties, and science fiction fans in general.<ref name=\"Malyk\" /> The film's trailer was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on 3 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=CLARA - TIFF Trailer (2018) - Troian Bellisario, Patrick J. Adams Sci-Fi Drama Movie HD |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7eIbm4cfA8M |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman gave a talk in advance of the film's premiere on the science behind the film at the Astronomy On Tap event in Toronto on 17 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"The Science of CLARA\" - Akash Sherman at Astronomy On Tap, Toronto HD |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nFL-thbPP0 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIsaac and Clara's use of publicly available data from NASA's TESS led to a \"''Clara''-inspired academic paper\" written by Welch and Moores and published in ''[[Research Notes of the American Astronomical Society]]''.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> The article, titled \"Simulating Transits at the L1 Point\", shares credit with Sherman.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Welch describes the relevant part of the film and the published paper:<blockquote>Near the end, when the characters are going over graphs of a star's light dimming from a transiting planet, there is a nice lump on the graph that draws the eye\u2014an object or artifact that becomes a very important plot point. Well, John Moores and I had figured out how such an object would appear in actual data, and that's part of what we ended up submitting as a paper. During the time we were developing this there was someone else, the astrophysicist Eric Gaidos, who also wrote a paper of a similar nature showing that our description was correct.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Release==\n''Clara'' premiered at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>[https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff-2018-canadian-films-rob-stewart/ \"TIFF 2018: Rob Stewart, Denys Arcand, Jennifer Baichwal films among Canadian titles\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', 1 August 2018.</ref> This was followed by a Canadian [[limited theatrical release]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" />\n\n===Distribution===\nD Films was responsible for ''Clara's'' Canadian theatrical distribution, while the CBC holds the television broadcast rights, and TMN holds the [[pay TV]] rights.<ref name=\"Pinto\" /> In 2019, the film was distributed by Screen Media Films in a limited theatrical release in the United States.<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Clara (2019) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Clara-(Canada)-(2019)#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Home media and streaming===\n''Clara'' is available on DVD<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (DVD) - Walmart.com |url=https://www.pinterest.com/pin/112027109497857701/ |website=[[Pinterest]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> from Screen Media Video<ref name=\"Numbers\" /> and Blu-ray.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.blu-ray.com/Clara/1139480/ |website=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film is available on [[video on demand]] platforms<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> such as [[Amazon Prime]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.amazon.com/Clara-Patrick-J-Adams/dp/B07RJ1T87C |website=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception== \n===Critical response===\n''Clara'' has a critic review score of 48% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 23 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (2018) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/clara_2018/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted score, the film has a score of 43 out of 100 based on six reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/clara |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAssigning the film 2 stars at [[RogerEbert.com]], Peter Sobczynski called the film \"peculiar and largely unsatisfying\" despite the ambitions displayed by Akash Sherman: \"the result is a weird muddle that's both too silly to be taken seriously and too staid to completely go off the beaten path.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sobczynski |first1=Peter |title=Clara |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/clara-2019 |website=RogerEbert.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Toronto critic Norman Wilner, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', though conceding the film has its moments, feels that the story stops where it ought to have begun.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Review: Toronto-set Clara stops just where it ought to begin |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/reviews/review-clara-akash-sherman/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Tara Thorne finds that ''Clara'' has \"outsized ideas that dominate and weaken the film beneath it\", lacking in humour but featuring too much \"data talk\", though it finally gains traction in the last twenty minutes, a \"big reveal\" that pays off but also sacrifices genuine emotions for \"dutifully plotted emotional beats.\" Having said all this, Thorne calls Sherman an \"assured director who clearly has big plans.\"<ref name=\"Thorne\">{{cite news |last1=Thorne |first1=Tara |title=Film review: Clara |url=https://www.thecoast.ca/halifax/film-review-clara/Content?oid=19372258 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=The Coast |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnlike Thorne, Don Shanahan finds the real life science as an \"interwoven backdrop\" provides a \"narrative boon for the science fiction of ''Clara''.\" Its \"sense of intelligence intertwines with the unpredictability found in the amorous reverberations of the human heart\", a combination which makes for an \"intimate and daring film experience\", a \"rare treat\" to have \"two narrative genres combined with smarts and affection.\"<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> Writing for ''[[Exclaim!]]'', Alex Hudson finds the science more intriguing than what he calls the film's philosophical musings, but, despite its flaws, it works as a mood piece: \"the colours are muted, the score is appropriately etherial, and it effectively captures Isaac's depression as he searches for meaning in his broken life. It gets under the skin even when it doesn't stimulate the mind.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hudson |first1=Alex |title='Clara' Is an Ambitious Hunt for the Meaning of Life |journal=[[Exclaim!]] |date=December 3, 2018 |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/tiff_review_clara_is_an_ambitious_hunt_for_the_meaning_of_life-directed_by_akash_sherman |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGiving the film a B rating, Jim Slotek calls ''Clara'' a \"solidly written\" film with an impressive \"level of sophistication in the storytelling\", benefiting from NASA\u2013provided photos and effects \"cannily\" used to give it \"the look of a much higher budgeted movie\".<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Scientific response===\nDoug Welch responded to Sherman's original script because \"it captures the excitement of revealing other planets and the potential for even identifying life elsewhere during our lifetime... it was clear to me that Akash understood a lot of the field and how it worked. You see this in small details, too, like ... using remote observations with a telescope in Chile.\"<ref name=\"Billings\" /> The film's trailer, due both to \"lush\" visual effects and such \"teasing science-savvy plot points\" attracted a lot of attention on social media from astronomers.<ref name=\"Billings\" />\n\n===Accolades===\n====Award====\n*[[Austin Film Festival]], 2018 \u2022 Jury Award for a Narrative Feature (Akash Sherman and James Ewasiuk)<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Winners |url=https://austinfilmfestival.com/blog/festival-and-conference/2018-winners/ |website=[[Austin Film Festival]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Nominations====\n;2018\n*[[Directors Guild of Canada]] Discovery Award;<ref>{{cite web |title=Discovery Award Long List 2018 |url=https://www.dgc.ca/en/national/news/discovery-award-long-list-2018/ |website=dcg.ca |publisher=[[Directors Guild of Canada]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[shortlist]]ed (1 of 4)<ref>{{cite web |title=Directors Guild presents: Visionaries at TIFF |url=https://www.dgc.ca/visionaries/visionaries/ |website=dcg.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] One to Watch Award and Best Best Actress in a Canadian Film<ref>{{cite web |title=Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award Nominations |url=https://theawardspsychic.blogspot.com/2018/12/vancouver-film-critics-circle-award.html |website=The Awards Psychic |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n;2019\n*[[Golden Trailer Awards]] Best Foreign Poster<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hipes |first1=Patrick |title=Golden Trailer Awards Nominations: \u2018A Star Is Born\u2019, Netflix Lead Way |journal=Deadline |date=9 May 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/golden-trailer-awards-nominees-2019-nominations-list-netflix-a-star-is-born-1202610742/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/CLARATheFilm/ Official page] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7eIbm4cfA8M Official trailer] on [[YouTube]]\n* {{IMDb title|6613878}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 romantic science fiction film directed by Akash Sherman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Clara\n| image          = Clara poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = Akash Sherman\n| producer       = Ari Lantos\n| writer         = \n{{Plainlist|\n*Akash Sherman\n*James Ewasiuk\n}}\n| starring       = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Patrick J. Adams]]\n*[[Troian Bellisario]]\n}}\n| music          = Jonathan Kawchuk\n| cinematography = Nick Haight\n| editing        = Matt Lyon\n| production companies = Serendipity Point Films ''in association with'' Distant Horizon\n| distributor    = D Films\n| released       = {{film date|2018|09|10|[[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = Canada, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Clara''''' is a 2018 Canadian-British [[science fiction film]] and the second feature film directed by Akash Sherman. The film stars husband and wife actors [[Patrick J. Adams]] and [[Troian Bellisario]], playing astrophysicist Isaac and itinerant artist Clara, who become close while searching for signs of intelligent life in the universe. The film is grounded in recent technological and theoretical advances, and attracted the attention of astronomers. The film received mixed reviews from critics, and out of a handful of nominations from various bodies, won an award from the [[Austin Film Festival]], \n\n==Plot==\nDr. Isaac Bruno holds a postdoctoral research fellowship in astrophysics at (fictional) Ontario University, in [[Toronto]]. His goal of finding signs of intelligent life in the universe has become an obsession, linked to an unspecified trauma in his personal life two years earlier. He has become increasingly antagonistic towards his students and has taken to misappropriating time on ground-based telescopes in Chile, intended for a colleague's research. His department head suspends him, denying him any access to the school's research facilities.\n\nThe [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] orbiting telescope is launched, providing enormous amounts of data that is shared with the world, in a community effort to analyze and find possible life on [[exoplanet]]s. Isaac posts flyers looking for an unpaid research assistant, offering nothing but room and board. His only response is from Clara, an uneducated artist who has lived a [[Bohemianism|Bohemian lifestyle]]. Clara has her own secrets, seen taking some type of medicine for an unspecified issue.\n\nIsaac focuses on results from [[Red dwarf|M dwarf]] stars, believing it to be a niche that no one else will bother with. When Clara finds a promising exoplanet, Isaac sneaks into the university in the night and lies to the telescope operators in Chile, claiming to have permission from his friend Charlie, to get more data on the planet.\n\nCharlie is furious, but also intrigued by the data results. He advises Isaac to contact Rebecca, Isaac's ex-wife, who holds an endowed chair at [[California Institute of Technology|Caltech]]. Clara convinces Isaac to contact Rebecca, despite his reluctance. The upheaval in their lives is finally revealed, when Rebecca tells Isaac that finding life will not bring back their dead baby son. She gets him some time on the [[W. M. Keck Observatory|Keck]] telescope. This results in proving that they have found a [[Planetary habitability|habitable planet candidate]].\n\nClara is falling in love with Isaac, but he has become jaded about love or anything else that can not be scientifically proven. She kisses him, then abruptly backs off when he starts to respond. When Charlie's wife has a baby, Isaac pontificates on how a minuscule change took his own son, and could equally change the entire universe. Clara reminds him that those same minuscule changes did result in his son existing at all. This leads to them finally becoming a couple. \n\nWhen they learn that someone else discovered \u201ctheir\u201d planet a week before them, Isaac becomes despondent. He soon decides to focus on finding direct evidence of life, rather than just a potentially habitable planet. In his obsession, he is blind to Clara's declining health, until Charlie chastises him. Isaac tells Clara it is time for him to stop his search, but she makes him ignore the data and focus on his inner connection to the universe. He is surprised when it works, but rejects it and her. She grabs her bag to leave - and collapses.\n\nAt the hospital, it is revealed that Clara has an autoimmune disease that is causing the complete breakdown of every organ and muscle in her body. The doctors are shocked that she can even walk or talk, and confirm she will soon be dead. Isaac stays at her bedside for her last few days. Moments before she dies, she tells him he is going to \u201csee it\u201d.\n\nA fresh batch of TESS data is released, and Isaac does \u201csee it\u201d - proof of a seemingly artificial object in coincident orbit with an exoplanet. He takes his findings to Charlie, who introduces him to Dr. Rickman, head of the TESS project. Two years later, at a press conference at the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory|JPL]], Dr. Rickman, Rebecca and Charlie explain that the data gathered now conclusively proves the existence of the artificial object, orbiting a star 200 light years distant, in turn proving the existence of intelligent alien life. Isaac is not in his assigned seat on the panel, choosing instead to spend time reminiscing about Clara.\n\nA few months later, Rebecca summons Isaac to the [[Search for extraterrestrial intelligence|SETI]] laboratory. She reveals that the aliens have sent a message&mdash;\u201cIsaac Bruno\u201d. He is present when the next message arrives &ndash; an audio file of a [[Bob Dylan]] song that he and Clara often listened to together. The film ends with Isaac smiling through his tears.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Patrick J. Adams]] as Dr. Isaac Bruno \n* [[Troian Bellisario]] as Clara\n* [[Ennis Esmer]] as Dr. Charlie Durant \n* [[Kristen Hager]] as Dr. Rebecca Jenkins \n* [[R. H. Thomson]] as Dr. Rickman\n* [[Jennifer Dale]] as Astrophysics Department Head\n\n==Themes and genre==\nA story about \"space and love\",<ref name=\"Slotek\">{{cite web |last1=Slotek |first1=Jim (interviewer) |title=Original-Cin Review/Q&A: Clara Filmmaker Shoots for the Stars (and Mostly Reaches \u2018Em, Too) |url=https://www.original-cin.ca/posts/2018/11/27/original-cin-reviewqampa-clara-filmmaker-shoots-for-the-stars-and-mostly-reaches-em-too |website=Original-Cin.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Akash Sherman titled the film ''Clara'' because the word means \"clear\" and \"bright,\" like a star: \"it was about this search for life among the stars.\"<ref name=\"Billings\">{{cite journal |last1=Billings |first1=Lee (interviewer) |title=''Clara'' Is a Story of Exoplanets, Existential Longing\u2014and Real Science |journal=[[Scientific American]] |date=11 October 2018 |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/clara-is-a-story-of-exoplanets-existential-longing-mdash-and-real-science1/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nSherman calls the film a \"[[high concept]]\" [[science fiction]] drama.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> He does not consider it a [[romantic film|romance]], but anticipated it would be marketed that way \"because the lead actors are married in real life\"; it is a love story to the extent that there is \"a binding bond between two characters\" who are \"just two people connecting for a bit.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Jim Slotek disagrees: \"Sherman's objections notwithstanding, ''Clara'' is a romance, albeit an interrupted one \u2014 kind of what you'd get if you crossed Carl Sagan's ''Contact'' with Erich Segal's ''Love Story.''\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nAt age 18, Sherman competed in the CineCoup Film Accelerator at the [[Banff World Media Festival]], where he won second place and attracted the attention of producer Ari Lantos.<ref name=\"Malyk\">{{cite journal |last1=Malyk |first1=Lauren |title=TIFF \u201918: The winning formula behind Akash Sherman\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=10 September 2018 |url=https://playbackonline.ca/2018/09/10/clara-a-sci-fi-stepping-stone/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman studied at [[Ryerson University]]'s film school for one year, where one day, at 19, he became determined to write a story, shutting himself in his dormitory room for seven hours.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> \n\n===Writing and development===\nFriends Sherman made at Ryerson worked with him on his debut, ''The Rocket List'', \"made on no budget ... on a four-day road trip with a camera,\"<ref name=\"Malyk\" /> as well as on ''Clara''.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Together with James Ewasiuk, a \"close collaborator\" who co-wrote ''The Rocket List'' with him, Sherman did four months of research on \"the Kepler telescope and transits and things like that.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Two years after they had met in Banff, Sherman ran into Lantos while pitching the draft script to Serendipity Point Films, from whom he received an option agreement the next day.<ref name=\"Malyk\" />\n\nBoth romantic leads also contributed ideas. Patrick Adams was involved with the project from an early stage, giving feedback to Sherman on his script, on character in particular, which the director began revising in earnest at age 20 and finished two years later.<ref name=\"Knight\" /> Troian Bellisario provided \"a similar depth for her character,\" and suggested a different ending for the film, a note which Sherman accepted: \"I had a different ending in mind, which I don't want to share because it's not as good.\"<ref name=\"Knight\" /> It was Bellisario who brought up [[quantum entanglement]] for one of the earlier drafts.<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\nThe project relied on three scientific advisors, Canadian astrophysicists John Moores and Doug Welch,<ref name=\"Billings\" /> at [[York University|York]] and [[McMaster University|McMaster]] universities respectively, and Barth Netterfeld of the [[University of Toronto]].<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Sherman and producer Ari Santos sent out an e-mail to Toronto-area physics and astronomy departments asking for help. Welch responded because there was so much \"real science\" in Sherman's script.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> During [[preproduction]] Welch spent time with Sherman, Adams, and Bellisario, explaining such concepts as the [[Fermi paradox]] and the [[Drake equation]] in relation to the mechanics of astronomical observing, and later also also suggested some dialogue exchanges.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> Accoding to Sherman, almost everything was vetted by the three consultants. \"It's so vetted, in fact, that the climactic discovery in the movie... turned out to be an original idea\", later published by the [[American Astronomical Society]].<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Financing===\n''Clara'' was produced by Serendipity Point in association with [[London]]-based Distant Horizon, with the support of [[Telefilm Canada]], the Ontario Media Development Corporation (Ontario Creates), the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], and [[Bell Media]]'s [[The Movie Network|TMN]].<ref name=\"Malyk\" /><ref name=\"Pinto\">{{cite journal |last1=Pinto |first1=Jordan |title=Production begins on Serendipity Point\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=7 March 2017 |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2017/03/07/production-begins-on-serendipity-points-clara/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] took place in [[Toronto]] and surrounding areas during the month of March in 2017.<ref name=\"Pinto\" /> Leads Adams and Bellisario were married a little earlier,<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite news |last1=Knight |first1=Chris |title=Akash Sherman looks to the cosmos for Clara, his second feature film |url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/akash-sherman-looks-to-the-cosmos-for-clara-his-second-feature-film |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[The National Post]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and spent a large portion of their [[honeymoon]] working on the film.<ref name=\"Collider\">{{cite web |title=Clara: Patrick J. Adams, Ari Lantos, and Director Akash Sherman on Their Grounded Sci-Fi Film [Collider interview] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFHtf7vTBmg |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020 |format=video}}</ref> \n\n====Locations====\nLocations included Sherman's [[alma mater]] Ryerson and the [[Mississauga]] campus of the University of Toronto for several NASA scenes, because of their \"spectacular buildings\".<ref name=\"Davidson\">{{cite journal |last1=Davidson |first1=Sonya (interviewer) |title=CLARA searches for life and connection beyond our world |url=https://torontoguardian.com/2018/12/clara-film-akash-sherman/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=Toronto Guardian |date=7 December 2018}}</ref> There are also outdoor scenes shot near [[Sugar Beach]], while a shot of the exterior of the [[McLaughlin Planetarium]] in Toronto was not included in the final cut of the theatrical release.<ref name=\"Davidson\" />\n\n====Visual effects and scientific accuracy====\nThe detection method and the specialized telescopes depicted in ''Clara'' are not fictional. The [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] space telescope is a 2018 upgrade of the [[Kepler Telescope]] which was used to discover over 4000 [[exoplanets]] in the decade since 2009.<ref name=\"Shanahan\">{{cite web |last1=Shanahan |first1=Don |title=Clara Grounds Solemnity and Sweetness Into Complicated Love Within Science Fiction |url=https://25yearslatersite.com/2019/09/19/clara-grounds-solemnity-and-sweetness-into-complicated-love-within-science-fiction/ |website=25YearsLaterSite.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman started his filmmaking career as [[visual effects]] artist, and all such shots in the film were made by him rather than by his cinematographer, sourced from [[NASA]]: shots of planets transiting a sun come from the [[Solar Dynamics Observatory]]; shots of nebulae come from the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] : \"I really wanted to show space honestly and in a way that would look familiar to people working in the field.\"<ref name=\"Billings\" />\n\n===Music===\nComposer Jonathan Kawchuk wrote a \"soft score\", complimenting musical selections by [[Bob Dylan]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> Kawchuk converted sounds from NASA's [[Voyager spacecraft]] into a [[synthesizer]], sounds which were \"baked into a lot of the tracks.\"<ref name=\"Billings\" />\n\n==Marketing and related works==\nLantos said that ''Clara'' was aimed at teenagers and women in their twenties, and science fiction fans in general.<ref name=\"Malyk\" /> The film's trailer was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on 3 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=CLARA - TIFF Trailer (2018) - Troian Bellisario, Patrick J. Adams Sci-Fi Drama Movie HD |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7eIbm4cfA8M |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman gave a talk in advance of the film's premiere on the science behind the film at the Astronomy On Tap event in Toronto on 17 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"The Science of CLARA\" - Akash Sherman at Astronomy On Tap, Toronto HD |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nFL-thbPP0 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIsaac and Clara's use of publicly available data from NASA's TESS led to a \"''Clara''-inspired academic paper\" written by Welch and Moores and published in ''[[Research Notes of the American Astronomical Society]]''.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> The article, titled \"Simulating Transits at the L1 Point\", shares credit with Sherman.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Welch describes the relevant part of the film and the published paper:<blockquote>Near the end, when the characters are going over graphs of a star's light dimming from a transiting planet, there is a nice lump on the graph that draws the eye\u2014an object or artifact that becomes a very important plot point. Well, John Moores and I had figured out how such an object would appear in actual data, and that's part of what we ended up submitting as a paper. During the time we were developing this there was someone else, the astrophysicist Eric Gaidos, who also wrote a paper of a similar nature showing that our description was correct.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Release==\n''Clara'' premiered at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>[https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff-2018-canadian-films-rob-stewart/ \"TIFF 2018: Rob Stewart, Denys Arcand, Jennifer Baichwal films among Canadian titles\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', 1 August 2018.</ref> This was followed by a Canadian [[limited theatrical release]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" />\n\n===Distribution===\nD Films was responsible for ''Clara's'' Canadian theatrical distribution, while the CBC holds the television broadcast rights, and TMN holds the [[pay TV]] rights.<ref name=\"Pinto\" /> In 2019, the film was distributed by Screen Media Films in a limited theatrical release in the United States.<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Clara (2019) |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Clara-(Canada)-(2019)#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Home media and streaming===\n''Clara'' is available on DVD<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (DVD) - Walmart.com |url=https://www.pinterest.com/pin/112027109497857701/ |website=[[Pinterest]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> from Screen Media Video<ref name=\"Numbers\" /> and Blu-ray.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.blu-ray.com/Clara/1139480/ |website=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film is available on [[video on demand]] platforms<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> such as [[Amazon Prime]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.amazon.com/Clara-Patrick-J-Adams/dp/B07RJ1T87C |website=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception== \n===Critical response===\n''Clara'' has a critic review score of 48% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 23 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (2018) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/clara_2018/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted score, the film has a score of 43 out of 100 based on six reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/clara |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAssigning the film 2 stars at [[RogerEbert.com]], Peter Sobczynski called the film \"peculiar and largely unsatisfying\" despite the ambitions displayed by Akash Sherman: \"the result is a weird muddle that's both too silly to be taken seriously and too staid to completely go off the beaten path.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sobczynski |first1=Peter |title=Clara |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/clara-2019 |website=RogerEbert.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Toronto critic Norman Wilner, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', though conceding the film has its moments, feels that the story stops where it ought to have begun.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Review: Toronto-set Clara stops just where it ought to begin |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/reviews/review-clara-akash-sherman/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Tara Thorne finds that ''Clara'' has \"outsized ideas that dominate and weaken the film beneath it\", lacking in humour but featuring too much \"data talk\", though it finally gains traction in the last twenty minutes, a \"big reveal\" that pays off but also sacrifices genuine emotions for \"dutifully plotted emotional beats.\" Having said all this, Thorne calls Sherman an \"assured director who clearly has big plans.\"<ref name=\"Thorne\">{{cite news |last1=Thorne |first1=Tara |title=Film review: Clara |url=https://www.thecoast.ca/halifax/film-review-clara/Content?oid=19372258 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=The Coast |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnlike Thorne, Don Shanahan finds the real life science as an \"interwoven backdrop\" provides a \"narrative boon for the science fiction of ''Clara''.\" Its \"sense of intelligence intertwines with the unpredictability found in the amorous reverberations of the human heart\", a combination which makes for an \"intimate and daring film experience\", a \"rare treat\" to have \"two narrative genres combined with smarts and affection.\"<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> Writing for ''[[Exclaim!]]'', Alex Hudson finds the science more intriguing than what he calls the film's philosophical musings, but, despite its flaws, it works as a mood piece: \"the colours are muted, the score is appropriately etherial, and it effectively captures Isaac's depression as he searches for meaning in his broken life. It gets under the skin even when it doesn't stimulate the mind.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hudson |first1=Alex |title='Clara' Is an Ambitious Hunt for the Meaning of Life |journal=[[Exclaim!]] |date=December 3, 2018 |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/tiff_review_clara_is_an_ambitious_hunt_for_the_meaning_of_life-directed_by_akash_sherman |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGiving the film a B rating, Jim Slotek calls ''Clara'' a \"solidly written\" with an impressive \"level of sophistication in the storytelling\", benefiting from NASA\u2013provided photos and effects \"cannily\" used to give it \"the look of a much higher budgeted movie\".<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Scientific response===\nDoug Welch responded to Sherman's original script because \"it captures the excitement of revealing other planets and the potential for even identifying life elsewhere during our lifetime... it was clear to me that Akash understood a lot of the field and how it worked. You see this in small details, too, like ... using remote observations with a telescope in Chile.\"<ref name=\"Billings\" /> The film's trailer, due both to \"lush\" visual effects and such \"teasing science-savvy plot points\" attracted a lot of attention on social media from astronomers.<ref name=\"Billings\" />\n\n===Accolades===\n====Award====\n*[[Austin Film Festival]], 2018 \u2022 Jury Award for a Narrative Feature (Akash Sherman and James Ewasiuk)<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Winners |url=https://austinfilmfestival.com/blog/festival-and-conference/2018-winners/ |website=[[Austin Film Festival]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Nominations====\n;2018\n*[[Directors Guild of Canada]] Discovery Award;<ref>{{cite web |title=Discovery Award Long List 2018 |url=https://www.dgc.ca/en/national/news/discovery-award-long-list-2018/ |website=dcg.ca |publisher=[[Directors Guild of Canada]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[shortlist]]ed (1 of 4)<ref>{{cite web |title=Directors Guild presents: Visionaries at TIFF |url=https://www.dgc.ca/visionaries/visionaries/ |website=dcg.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] One to Watch Award and Best Best Actress in a Canadian Film<ref>{{cite web |title=Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award Nominations |url=https://theawardspsychic.blogspot.com/2018/12/vancouver-film-critics-circle-award.html |website=The Awards Psychic |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n;2019\n*[[Golden Trailer Awards]] Best Foreign Poster<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hipes |first1=Patrick |title=Golden Trailer Awards Nominations: \u2018A Star Is Born\u2019, Netflix Lead Way |journal=Deadline |date=9 May 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/golden-trailer-awards-nominees-2019-nominations-list-netflix-a-star-is-born-1202610742/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/CLARATheFilm/ Official page] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7eIbm4cfA8M Official trailer] on [[YouTube]]\n* {{IMDb title|6613878}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n", "name_user": "ZarhanFastfire", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical response", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Brett Smiley", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2019}}\n'''Brett Smiley''' (September 25, 1955 \u2013 January 8, 2016)<ref name=billboard>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/obituary/6836578/brett-smiley-dead |title= Glam Rock Cult Hero Brett Smiley Dies at Age 60|date=January 11, 2016|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"death\">[http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20160111/NEWS02/160119811 Glam rock cult hero Brett Smiley dies in NYC at age 60]: ''Herald Net''. Retrieved January 12, 2016.</ref> was an American [[singer-songwriter]] who was active in the UK during the [[glam rock]] era of the early 1970s. Smiley released one single, \"Va Va Va Voom,\" and made an appearance on the [[Russell Harty]] television show, where he performed the song \"Space Ace\". One posthumous vinyl album \"Brett Smiley Sunset Tower\" was released in 2019 in a limited edition of 500 for Record Store Day.\n\n<br />\n\n==Career==\nSmiley began his career as a child actor, playing [[Oliver Twist|Oliver]] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].<ref name=billboard/>\n\nIn 1974, Smiley\u2014who, at the time, was managed and produced by [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] manager [[Andrew Loog Oldham]]\u2014recorded an album, ''Breathlessly Brett.'' The album, which included  the songs \"Va Va Va Voom\" and \"Space Ace\", remained unreleased until 2003, when [[RPM Records (United Kingdom)|RPM Records]] included it as part of its Lipsmackin' 70s collection.\n\nSmiley also starred as the Prince, in the 1977 American erotic musical comedy ''[[Cinderella (1977 film)|Cinderella.]]''\n\nIn 2004, rock biographer [[Nina Antonia]] published a book about Smiley, ''The Prettiest Star: Whatever Happened to Brett Smiley.''\n\nSmiley still performed occasionally until 2015 in [[New York City]], and was recording songs for a new CD. He died on January 8, 2016, after a lengthy battle with HIV and hepatitis.<ref name=billboard/><ref name=\"death\" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Thompson |url=http://www.goldminemag.com/features/brett-smiley-va-va-voom-september-25-1955-january-7-2016 |title=Brett Smiley - Va Va Voom (September 25, 1955 - January 7, 2016) - Goldmine Magazine |website=Goldminemag.com |date=2016-01-07 |accessdate=2016-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==''Breathlessly Brett'' track listing==\n{{Infobox album\n| italic_title = no\n| name         = Breathlessly Brett\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = Brett Smiley\n| cover        =\n| alt          = A photograph of a woman seated on a chair with the artist name and album title written next to her\n| released     = {{start date|2003|df=yes}}\n| recorded     = 1974\n| venue        =\n| studio       =\n| genre        =\n| length       =\n| label        = [[RPM Records (United Kingdom)|RPM]]\n| producer     = [[Andrew Loog Oldham]]\n| prev_title   =\n| prev_year    =\n| next_title   =\n| next_year    =\n}}\n#\"Brett's Lullaby\"\n#\"Highty Tighty\"\n#\"Space Ace\"\n#\"April in Paris\"\n#\"Solitaire\"\n#\"Va Va Va Voom\"\n#\"Run for the Sun\"\n#\"[[I Want to Hold Your Hand]]\" ([[Lennon\u2013McCartney]])\n#\"Pre-Columbian Love\"\n#\"Queen of Hearts\"\n#\"I Can't Help Myself\"/\"Over the Rainbow\"\n#\"Young at Heart\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Nina Antonia |title=The Prettiest Star: Whatever Happened to Brett Smiley |publisher=SAF Publishing Ltd |location= |year=2005 |pages= |isbn=0-946719-72-1 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1080133|name=Brett Smiley}}\n*[http://www.boingboing.net/2008/10/16/whatever-happened-to.html Whatever happened to Brett Smiley?]\n*[http://www.magnetmagazine.com/2011/04/21/from-the-desk-of-kristian-hoffman-smiley-come-lately-my-tardy-love-for-brett/  Magnet Magazine Article About Brett Smiley by Kristian Hoffman]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j9xIvGSj88g Youtube Brett Smiley on the Russell Harty show]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSOR