 WP, Hofstra CL, Jiang W, Nguyen S, Riley JP, Sun S, Williams KN, Edwards JP, Karlsson L | date = Apr 2004 | title = A potent and selective histamine H4 receptor antagonist with anti-inflammatory properties | url = | journal = Journal of Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics | volume = 309 | issue = 1| pages = 404\u201313 | pmid = 14722321 | doi = 10.1124/jpet.103.061754 }}</ref> and has been demonstrated to be superior to traditional antihistamines in the treatment of [[pruritus]] (itching).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Dunford PJ, Williams KN, Desai PJ, Karlsson L, McQueen D, Thurmond RL | date = Jan 2007 | title = Histamine H4 receptor antagonists are superior to traditional antihistamines in the attenuation of experimental pruritus | url = | journal = Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology | volume = 119 | issue = 1| pages = 176\u201383 | pmid = 17208599 | doi = 10.1016/j.jaci.2006.08.034 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[VUF-6002]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Histaminergics}}\n{{Piperazines}}\n\n[[Category:Carboxamides]]\n[[Category:Chloroarenes]]\n[[Category:H4 receptor antagonists]]\n[[Category:Indoles]]\n[[Category:Johnson & Johnson brands]]\n[[Category:Piperazines]]\n\n\n{{pharma-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 394360889\n| IUPAC_name = 5-chloro-2-[(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)carbonyl]-1''H''-indole\n| image = JNJ-7777120.svg\n| alt = Skeletal formula of JNJ-7777120\n| image2 = JNJ-7777120-3D-spacefill.png\n| alt2 = Ball-and-stick model of the JNJ-7777120 molecule\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| routes_of_administration =  \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 459168-41-3\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 4H1AU2V37X\n| PubChem = 4908365\n| IUPHAR_ligand = 1278\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 129198\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 4090750\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=14 | H=16 | Cl=1 | N=3 | O=1 \n| molecular_weight = 277.749 g/mol\n| smiles = C3CN(C)CCN3C(=O)c(cc1c2)[nH]c1ccc2Cl\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C14H16ClN3O/c1-17-4-6-18(7-5-17)14(19)13-9-10-8-11(15)2-3-12(10)16-13/h2-3,8-9,16H,4-7H2,1H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = HUQJRYMLJBBEDO-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| synonyms = <small>1-[(5-chloro-1H-indol-2-yl)carbonyl]-4-methylpiperazine</small>\n}}\n\n'''JNJ-7777120''' is a drug being developed by [[Johnson & Johnson Pharmaceutical Research & Development]] which acts as a potent and selective [[Receptor antagonist|antagonist]] at the [[histamine H4 receptor|histamine H<sub>4</sub> receptor]].<ref name=\"pmid18639542\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Jiang W, Lim HD, Zhang M, etal |title=Cloning and pharmacological characterization of the dog histamine H(4) receptor |journal=Eur. J. Pharmacol. |volume= 592|issue= 1\u20133|pages= 26\u201332|date=July 2008 |pmid=18639542 |doi=10.1016/j.ejphar.2008.06.095 }}</ref> It has [[anti-inflammatory]] effects,<ref>Thurmond RL, Desai PJ, Dunford PJ, Fung-Leung WP, Hofstra CL, Jiang W, Nguyen S, Riley JP, Sun S, Williams KN, Edwards JP, Karlsson L. A potent and selective histamine H4 receptor antagonist with anti-inflammatory properties. ''Journal of Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics''. 2004 Apr;309(1):404-13. {{PMID|14722321}}</ref> and has been demonstrated to be superior to traditional antihistamines in the treatment of [[pruritus]] (itching).<ref>Dunford PJ, Williams KN, Desai PJ, Karlsson L, McQueen D, Thurmond RL. Histamine H4 receptor antagonists are superior to traditional antihistamines in the attenuation of experimental pruritus. ''Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology''. 2007 Jan;119(1):176-83. {{PMID|17208599}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[VUF-6002]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Histaminergics}}\n{{Piperazines}}\n\n[[Category:Carboxamides]]\n[[Category:Chloroarenes]]\n[[Category:H4 receptor antagonists]]\n[[Category:Indoles]]\n[[Category:Johnson & Johnson brands]]\n[[Category:Piperazines]]\n\n{{pharma-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JNJ-7777120"}
{"title_page": "That Brennan Girl", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = That Brennan Girl\n| image_size     = \n| image          = That Brennan Girl FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = 1951 theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Alfred Santell]]\n| producer       = Alfred Santell\n| story          = [[Adela Rogers St. Johns]]\n| screenplay     = [[Doris Anderson (screenwriter)|Doris Anderson]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]]<br />[[Mona Freeman]]<br />[[William Marshall (bandleader)|William Marshall]]<br />[[June Duprez]]\n| music          = [[George Antheil]]\n| cinematography = [[Jack A. Marta]]\n| editing        = [[Arthur Roberts (editor)|Arthur Roberts]]\n| studio         = [[Republic Pictures]]\n| distributor    = Republic Pictures\n| released       = {{film date|1946|12|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $750,000<ref name=brady>{{citation|last=Brady|first=Thomas F.|title=Santell, Republic cancel contract: Producer and company decide to part after disagreement on budget for new film\" |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 23, 1947|page=18}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''That Brennan Girl''''', also known as '''''Tough Girl''''', is a 1946 [[Melodrama#Film|melodrama film]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/25007|title=That Brennan Girl (1946)|work=AFI Catalog|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|year=2019|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> produced and directed by [[Alfred Santell]] and starring [[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]], [[Mona Freeman]], [[William Marshall (bandleader)|William Marshall]], and [[June Duprez]]. The story concerns a young woman raised in an unwholesome environment who joins a [[Confidence trick|confidence racket]] run by one of her mother's friends. She agrees to marry the victim of one of her scams, becomes a war widow, and is left to raise a baby, but abandons it each evening to go out dancing. After the child suffers an accident in her absence, she is charged with child neglect and loses custody. She mends her ways by devotedly caring for an abandoned infant and meets up again with the con man, who has also reformed after a prison stint, and together they build a new life. The film was the last work of director Santell and the last leading role for actor Dunn.<ref name=moma>{{cite web |url= https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/4029|title=''That Brennan Girl''. 1946. Directed by Alfred Santell|publisher=[[Museum of Modern Art]]|year=2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 a re-mastered and restored print by [[Paramount Pictures]], [[The Film Foundation]], and [[Martin Scorsese]] was screened at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] as part of the museum's program of showcasing 30 restored films from the library of [[Republic Pictures]], curated by Scorsese.\n\n==Plot==\nOn [[Mother's Day]] 1946, a woman known as Ziggy Brennan looks back on her life. \n\nEight years earlier, her vain and corrupt mother Natalie asks Ziggy to pretend they are sisters. Together they trick men out of money. Ziggy takes a liking to a con artist, Denny Reagan, and steals a soldier's watch that Denny admires. The watch's inscription, showing it is a gift from the boy's mother, gives Denny a guilty conscience, so Ziggy returns it to Mart Neilson, the soldier. He asks her on a date, which leads to marriage. Two days later, Neilson is shipped off to war. He is killed in action while Ziggy is pregnant with their child.\n\nZiggy is warned by Natalie after the birth of baby Martha that she is not fit for motherhood. Denny is now doing time in a penitentiary, so he is no help either. Ziggy likes to go out dancing every night, leaving Martha with an irresponsible young babysitter. While the babysitter sneaks out to be with her boyfriend, Martha tumbles out of her crib and is nearly strangled by the bedsheets. A landlady's testimony results in the baby being sent to a juvenile ward. Ziggy is given a suspended sentence for child neglect, but is forbidden from having contact with her child. Denny's mother tracks down Ziggy and encourages her to pray for salvation.\n\nBy the time Denny leaves prison, he is a reformed man. He tracks down Ziggy and finds that she has taken in an abandoned infant and is caring for it, having named him Denny. Together they appeal to the court for a second chance, then leave together with both children, united as a family.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]] as Denny Reagan\n* [[Mona Freeman]] as Ziggy Brennan\n* [[William Marshall (bandleader)|William Marshall]] as CPO Martin J. 'Mart' Neilson\n* [[June Duprez]] as Natalie Brennan\n* [[Frank Jenks]] as Joe the cabbie\n* Dorothy Vaughan as Mrs. Reagan, Denny's mother\n* [[Charles Arnt]] as Fred, Natalie's second husband\n* [[Rosalind Ivan]] as Mrs. Merryman, the landlady\n* [[Fay Helm]] as Helen, Ziggy's neighbor\n* [[Bill Kennedy (actor)|Bill Kennedy]] as Arthur, Helen's husband\n* [[Connie Leon]] as Miss Jane\n* [[Edythe Elliott]] as Miss Unity\n* [[Sarah Padden]] as Mrs. Graves, the nice landlady\n* Jean Stevens as Dottie, Natalie's friend\n* [[Lucien Littlefield]] as the florist\n* [[Marion Martin]] as Marion, Natalie's girlfriend\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nThe screenplay by [[Doris Anderson]] was based on a story by [[Adela Rogers St. John]].<ref name=minn/> The script underwent several rewrites on the orders of [[Joseph I. Breen]], director of the [[Production Code Administration]].<ref name=afi/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:That Brennan Girl (1946) still 1.jpg|right|220px|thumb|[[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]] and [[Mona Freeman]] in ''That Brennan Girl'']]\nThe ''[[Times Colonist]]'' noted that James Dunn and June Duprez were both [[Typecasting|cast against type]]. Dunn, coming off his Oscar-winning performance as an alcoholic father in ''[[A Tree Grows in Brooklyn (1945 film)|A Tree Grows in Brooklyn]]'' (1945), here played \"a daring, but sentimental young gangster\".<ref name=col/> Duprez, typically viewed by film producers as \"an Oriental princess type\", was cast as \"a hardboiled and rowdy mother\".<ref name=col>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897206/times-colonist/|title='That Brennan Girl' On Dominion Screen|newspaper=[[Times Colonist]]|date=August 26, 1947|page=9|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> \n\nMona Freeman was cast in the lead role of Ziggy after an extensive talent search. In December 1945, director Alfred Santell returned from a New York trip during which he tested dozens of actresses; he was said to be looking for \"some girl who looked like [[Lana Turner]] or [[Gene Tierney]] and could act like [[Sylvia Sidney]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897666/st-louis-globe-democrat/|title=Looking for Ziggy Brennan|first=Lucy|last=Greenbaum|newspaper=[[St. Louis Globe-Democrat]]|date=December 18, 1945|page=9| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Freeman, aged 21, was ultimately signed, having played mostly juvenile parts in her short film career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48999332/fort-worth-star-telegram/|title=Mona Freeman Featured In 'That Brennan Girl'|first=Gita|last=Bumpass|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|date=February 26, 1947|page=7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\nMartha as a 3-year-old was played by Colette Granlund from [[Mendocino County, California|Mendocino County]]. She was spotted by a talent scout while visiting San Francisco's [[Golden Gate Park]] with her parents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897401/mendocino-coast-beacon/|title=Little Colette, 3, Plays in Movie Scenes|newspaper=[[Mendocino Beacon|Mendocino Coast Beacon]]|date=June 15, 1946|page=7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nProduction took place between late April and early June 1946.<ref name=afi/> Much of the shooting took place on location in the streets and harbor of [[San Francisco]].<ref name=afi/><ref name=charlotte/> The actors blended in with passersby and were filmed in street scenes by a [[hidden camera]] enclosed in a slow-moving truck trailing behind them, and in sidewalk close-ups by a camera hidden in a baby carriage.<ref name=charlotte>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897373/the-charlotte-news/|title=Dunn Trying For Another Comeback In 'Brennan Girl'|first=Emery|last=Wister|newspaper=[[The Charlotte News]]|date=September 7, 1946|page=11|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Unable to find a suitable house in San Francisco, the film crew used a stately Old California home in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] for the scene in which the racketeers carry out an expensive sofa into their truck.<ref name=charlotte/> \n\nDunn's mother died in [[Los Angeles]] during the filming, with Dunn at her side.<ref name=jesse>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48495700/the-sacramento-bee/|title=Mother Of James Dunn, Film Actor, Succumbs|author=Associated Press|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=May 31, 1946|page=9| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref><ref name=charlotte/>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released on December 23, 1946.<ref name=afi/>\n\nIn 1951, the film was re-edited and re-released under the title ''Tough Girl''.<ref name=afi/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nCritics generally praised the acting and direction but decried the plot and script, characterizing it as a \"seamy-side melodrama\"<ref name=minn>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901421/the-minneapolis-star/|title=The Show Window|first=Bob|last=Murphy|date=June 27, 1947|page=17|newspaper=[[The Minneapolis Star]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> and \"a run-of-the-mill problem melodrama\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897320/star-tribune/|title=Newly Current|newspaper=Star Tribune|location=[[Minneapolis]], Minnesota|date=June 29, 1947|page=58| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' wrote: \"Jimmy Dunn does as well as anyone could, considering the plot and the script, and Mona Freeman is appealing, but the whole business is leaden and definitely second class fare\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897296/chicago-tribune/|title='Brennan Girl' Is Second Rate as Movie Fare|first=Mae |last=Tin\u00e9e|date=February 22, 1947|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[St. Louis Globe Democrat]]'' found it difficult to make sense of the story and its message. Ziggy starts out earning audience sympathy for her difficult upbringing, but loses it by accepting her mother's advice that \"the path of easy virtue is the easy way\". Denny is at the same time a [[Racket (crime)|racketeer]] and \"a likeable Irishman who is ever so good to his mother\". After Ziggy suffers for her hedonistic lifestyle and Denny serves time in prison, their reunion seems to convey that \"their romance should be both logical and appealing\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897440/st-louis-globe-democrat/|title=At the Movies|first=Herbert L.|last=Monk|newspaper=[[St. Louis Globe Democrat]]|date=December 26, 1946|page=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' called Dunn's  performance \"restrained and believable \u2026 [b]ut this role doesn't give him a chance to show the stuff he did in ''A Tree Grows in Brooklyn''\".<ref name=gazette>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897532/pittsburgh-post-gazette/|title='That Brennan Girl'|author=E. R.|date=December 18, 1946|page=10|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[The San Francisco Examiner]]'' commended Dunn for being \"more than adequate in an inadequate role\".<ref name=examiner>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897560/the-san-francisco-examiner/|title=Mona Freeman Scores in 'That Brennan Girl'|first=Hortense|last=Morton|date=December 14, 1946|newspaper=[[The San Francisco Examiner]]|page=12|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> \n\nFreeman's performance received harsher scrutiny in light of the extremes of personality she was required to play. ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' wrote: \n<blockquote>Miss Freeman looks lovely, innocent, and very young, at all times. This is remarkable when you consider that she has to impersonate a thief, a devoted young mother, a brazen mantrap, an industrious housewife, a shoplifter, a war widow, a bar butterfly, a confidence woman and a specimen of fine womanhood, and all within 95 minutes. The only way Republic could get this role played right would be to have [[Katharine Cornell]], [[Helen Hayes]], [[June Havoc]] and [[Ina Claire]] do it in relays. Even then we wouldn't like it.<ref name=bsun>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897273/the-baltimore-sun/|title='Brennan Girl'|first=Donald|last=Kirkley|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=January 18, 1947|page=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' wrote: \"Miss Freeman should get A-plus for her sincere attempt to play a bad girl. Fine features, a sensitive face and a touch of gentleness about her makes it doubtful casting. A tougher brat would have filled the role better\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897173/fort-worth-star-telegram/|title=Social Problem Rates Tawdry, Emotional 'A'|first=Ida Belle|last=Hicks|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=February 26, 1947|page=10| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' panned Freeman's acting as \"immature\".<ref name=gazette/> At the same time, it gave kudos to the performances of actresses [[June Duprez]], Dorothy Vaughn, and [[Rosalind Ivan]], calling the latter's portrayal of the landlady \"excellent\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897532/pittsburgh-post-gazette/|title='That Brennan Girl'|author=E. R.|date=December 18, 1946|page=10|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]'' also singled out actresses who played minor characters \u2013 including the babysitter ([[Shirley Mills]] in an uncredited role<ref name=afi/>), two lonely women, and an assortment of neighbors \u2013 for praise.<ref name=suntele/>\n\nSantell's direction received positive mention in several reviews. The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the film \"reminiscent of the late '20's in direction (by Old-Timer Alfred Santell) and 'feel'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49011446/the-los-angeles-times/|title=Delinquency Drama and 'Rogue' Billed|first=Philip K.|last=Scheuer|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 8, 1946|page=7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]'' complimented Santell's \"minor directorial flourishes\", adding, \"As a matter of fact, his contribution alone puts the picture into the general category of worth seeing\".<ref name=suntele>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897502/pittsburgh-sun-telegraph/|title=Dunn Film Starts Run|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]|date=December 18, 1946|page=28| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> ''[[The Minneapolis Star]]'' called [[George Antheil]]'s score \"outstanding\".<ref name=minn/>\n\n==Restoration==\nA re-mastered, restored print of ''That Brennan Girl'' by [[Paramount Pictures]], [[The Film Foundation]], and [[Martin Scorsese]] was screened at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA) in February 2018. The screening was the first in a two-part series titled ''Martin Scorsese Presents Republic Rediscovered: New Restorations from Paramount Pictures'', which showcased 30 restored films from the library of [[Republic Pictures]].<ref name=natalie/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.moma.org/calendar/film/3932|title=Film Series|publisher=[[Museum of Modern Art]]|year=2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hayes|first=Dade|title=Martin Scorsese, Paramount Back MoMA Republic Pictures Screening Series|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/martin-scorsese-paramount-back-moma-republic-pictures-screening-series-1202240835/|accessdate=January 14, 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> The restoration was released on the [[Apple TV (software)|Apple TV app]] the following year.<ref name=natalie>{{cite web |url= http://www.film-foundation.org/apple-tv-republic|title=Paramount Releases Martin Scorsese-Curated Republic Pictures Slate for Digital Purchase|first=Natalie|last=Jarvey|date=September 9, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2020|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\nThe MoMA website calls the film \"[u]naccountably overlooked\" and a \"resonant, formally inventive film\".<ref name=moma/> According to ''[[The Village Voice]]'', the work displays a host of Santell's creative directorial touches, such as \"scenes played in silhouette, in pantomime as the camera watches through a window, on two or three levels of a staircase in a couple of scenes reminiscent of ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]''\".<ref name=village>{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/02/06/restorations-from-republic-pictures-reveal-a-studio-that-got-its-hands-dirty/|title= Restorations From Republic Pictures Reveal a Studio That Got Its Hands Dirty|first=Farran Smith|last=Nehme|date=February 6, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020|work=[[The Village Voice]]}}</ref> This report concluded that the film demonstrated \"the kind of creativity that once flourished at Republic\".<ref name=village/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0039020|That Brennan Girl}}\n*{{Allmovie title|49251}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|that_brennan_girl}}\n*{{Internet Archive film|that_brennan_girl|That Brennan Girl}}\n\n[[Category:1946 films]]\n[[Category:Melodramas]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Alfred Santell]]\n[[Category:Films scored by George Antheil]]\n[[Category:Republic Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = That Brennan Girl\n| image_size     = \n| image          = That Brennan Girl FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = 1951 theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Alfred Santell]]\n| producer       = Alfred Santell\n| story          = [[Adela Rogers St. Johns]]\n| screenplay     = [[Doris Anderson (screenwriter)|Doris Anderson]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]]<br />[[Mona Freeman]]<br />[[William Marshall (bandleader)|William Marshall]]<br />[[June Duprez]]\n| music          = [[George Antheil]]\n| cinematography = [[Jack A. Marta]]\n| editing        = [[Arthur Roberts (editor)|Arthur Roberts]]\n| studio         = [[Republic Pictures]]\n| distributor    = Republic Pictures\n| released       = {{film date|1946|12|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $750,000<ref name=brady>{{citation|last=Brady|first=Thomas F.|title=Santell, Republic cancel contract: Producer and company decide to part after disagreement on budget for new film\" |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 23, 1947|page=18}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''That Brennan Girl''''', also known as '''''Tough Girl''''', is a 1946 [[Melodrama#Film|melodrama film]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/25007|title=That Brennan Girl (1946)|work=AFI Catalog|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|year=2019|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> produced and directed by [[Alfred Santell]] and starring [[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]], [[Mona Freeman]], [[William Marshall (bandleader)|William Marshall]], and [[June Duprez]]. The story concerns a young woman raised in an unwholesome environment who joins a [[Confidence trick|confidence racket]] run by one of her mother's friends. She agrees to marry the victim of one of her scams, becomes a war widow, and is left to raise a baby, but abandons it each evening to go out dancing. After the child suffers an accident in her absence, she is charged with child neglect and loses custody. She mends her ways by devotedly caring for an abandoned infant and meets up again with the con man, who has also reformed after a prison stint, and together they build a new life. The film was the last work of director Santell and the last leading role for actor Dunn.<ref name=moma>{{cite web |url= https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/4029|title=''That Brennan Girl''. 1946. Directed by Alfred Santell|publisher=[[Museum of Modern Art]]|year=2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 a re-mastered and restored print by [[Paramount Pictures]], [[The Film Foundation]], and [[Martin Scorsese]] was screened at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] as part of the museum's program of showcasing 30 restored films from the library of [[Republic Pictures]], curated by Scorsese.\n\n==Plot==\nOn [[Mother's Day]] 1946, a woman known as Ziggy Brennan looks back on her life. \n\nEight years earlier, her vain and corrupt mother Natalie asks Ziggy to pretend they are sisters. Together they trick men out of money. Ziggy takes a liking to a con artist, Denny Reagan, and steals a soldier's watch that Denny admires. The watch's inscription, showing it is a gift from the boy's mother, gives Denny a guilty conscience, so Ziggy returns it to Mart Neilson, the soldier. He asks her on a date, which leads to marriage. Two days later, Neilson is shipped off to war. He is killed in action while Ziggy is pregnant with their child.\n\nZiggy is warned by Natalie after the birth of baby Martha that she is not fit for motherhood. Denny is now doing time in a penitentiary, so he is no help either. Ziggy likes to go out dancing every night, leaving Martha with an irresponsible young babysitter. While the babysitter sneaks out to be with her boyfriend, Martha tumbles out of her crib and is nearly strangled by the bedsheets. A landlady's testimony results in the baby being sent to a juvenile ward. Ziggy is given a suspended sentence for child neglect, but is forbidden from having contact with her child. Denny's mother tracks down Ziggy and encourages her to pray for salvation.\n\nBy the time Denny leaves prison, he is a reformed man. He tracks down Ziggy and finds that she has taken in an abandoned infant and is caring for it, having named him Denny. Together they appeal to the court for a second chance, then leave together with both children, united as a family.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]] as Denny Reagan\n* [[Mona Freeman]] as Ziggy Brennan\n* [[William Marshall (bandleader)|William Marshall]] as CPO Martin J. 'Mart' Neilson\n* [[June Duprez]] as Natalie Brennan\n* [[Frank Jenks]] as Joe the cabbie\n* Dorothy Vaughan as Mrs. Reagan, Denny's mother\n* [[Charles Arnt]] as Fred, Natalie's second husband\n* [[Rosalind Ivan]] as Mrs. Merryman, the landlady\n* [[Fay Helm]] as Helen, Ziggy's neighbor\n* [[Bill Kennedy (actor)|Bill Kennedy]] as Arthur, Helen's husband\n* [[Connie Leon]] as Miss Jane\n* [[Edythe Elliott]] as Miss Unity\n* [[Sarah Padden]] as Mrs. Graves, the nice landlady\n* Jean Stevens as Dottie, Natalie's friend\n* [[Lucien Littlefield]] as the florist\n* [[Marion Martin]] as Marion, Natalie's girlfriend\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nThe screenplay by [[Doris Anderson]] was based on a story by [[Adela Rogers St. John]].<ref name=minn/> The script underwent several rewrites on the orders of [[Joseph I. Breen]], director of the [[Production Code Administration]].<ref name=afi/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:That Brennan Girl (1946) still 1.jpg|right|220px|thumb|[[James Dunn (actor)|James Dunn]] and [[Mona Freeman]] in ''That Brennan Girl'']]\nThe ''[[Times Colonist]]'' noted that James Dunn and June Duprez were both [[Typecasting|cast against type]]. Dunn, coming off his Oscar-winning performance as an alcoholic father in ''[[A Tree Grows in Brooklyn (film)|A Tree Grows in Brooklyn]]'' (1945), here played \"a daring, but sentimental young gangster\".<ref name=col/> Duprez, typically viewed by film producers as \"an Oriental princess type\", was cast as \"a hardboiled and rowdy mother\".<ref name=col>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897206/times-colonist/|title='That Brennan Girl' On Dominion Screen|newspaper=[[Times Colonist]]|date=August 26, 1947|page=9|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> \n\nMona Freeman was cast in the lead role of Ziggy after an extensive talent search. In December 1945, director Alfred Santell returned from a New York trip during which he tested dozens of actresses; he was said to be looking for \"some girl who looked like [[Lana Turner]] or [[Gene Tierney]] and could act like [[Sylvia Sidney]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897666/st-louis-globe-democrat/|title=Looking for Ziggy Brennan|first=Lucy|last=Greenbaum|newspaper=[[St. Louis Globe-Democrat]]|date=December 18, 1945|page=9| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Freeman, aged 21, was ultimately signed, having played mostly juvenile parts in her short film career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48999332/fort-worth-star-telegram/|title=Mona Freeman Featured In 'That Brennan Girl'|first=Gita|last=Bumpass|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|date=February 26, 1947|page=7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\nMartha as a 3-year-old was played by Colette Granlund from [[Mendocino County, California|Mendocino County]]. She was spotted by a talent scout while visiting San Francisco's [[Golden Gate Park]] with her parents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897401/mendocino-coast-beacon/|title=Little Colette, 3, Plays in Movie Scenes|newspaper=[[Mendocino Beacon|Mendocino Coast Beacon]]|date=June 15, 1946|page=7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nProduction took place between late April and early June 1946.<ref name=afi/> Much of the shooting took place on location in the streets and harbor of [[San Francisco]].<ref name=afi/><ref name=charlotte/> The actors blended in with passersby and were filmed in street scenes by a [[hidden camera]] enclosed in a slow-moving truck trailing behind them, and in sidewalk close-ups by a camera hidden in a baby carriage.<ref name=charlotte>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897373/the-charlotte-news/|title=Dunn Trying For Another Comeback In 'Brennan Girl'|first=Emery|last=Wister|newspaper=[[The Charlotte News]]|date=September 7, 1946|page=11|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Unable to find a suitable house in San Francisco, the film crew used a stately Old California home in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] for the scene in which the racketeers carry out an expensive sofa into their truck.<ref name=charlotte/> \n\nDunn's mother died in [[Los Angeles]] during the filming, with Dunn at her side.<ref name=jesse>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48495700/the-sacramento-bee/|title=Mother Of James Dunn, Film Actor, Succumbs|author=Associated Press|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=May 31, 1946|page=9| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref><ref name=charlotte/>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released on December 23, 1946.<ref name=afi/>\n\nIn 1951, the film was re-edited and re-released under the title ''Tough Girl''.<ref name=afi/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nCritics generally praised the acting and direction but decried the plot and script, characterizing it as a \"seamy-side melodrama\"<ref name=minn>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901421/the-minneapolis-star/|title=The Show Window|first=Bob|last=Murphy|date=June 27, 1947|page=17|newspaper=[[The Minneapolis Star]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> and \"a run-of-the-mill problem melodrama\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897320/star-tribune/|title=Newly Current|newspaper=Star Tribune|location=[[Minneapolis]], Minnesota|date=June 29, 1947|page=58| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' wrote: \"Jimmy Dunn does as well as anyone could, considering the plot and the script, and Mona Freeman is appealing, but the whole business is leaden and definitely second class fare\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897296/chicago-tribune/|title='Brennan Girl' Is Second Rate as Movie Fare|first=Mae |last=Tin\u00e9e|date=February 22, 1947|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[St. Louis Globe Democrat]]'' found it difficult to make sense of the story and its message. Ziggy starts out earning audience sympathy for her difficult upbringing, but loses it by accepting her mother's advice that \"the path of easy virtue is the easy way\". Denny is at the same time a [[Racket (crime)|racketeer]] and \"a likeable Irishman who is ever so good to his mother\". After Ziggy suffers for her hedonistic lifestyle and Denny serves time in prison, their reunion seems to convey that \"their romance should be both logical and appealing\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897440/st-louis-globe-democrat/|title=At the Movies|first=Herbert L.|last=Monk|newspaper=[[St. Louis Globe Democrat]]|date=December 26, 1946|page=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' called Dunn's  performance \"restrained and believable \u2026 [b]ut this role doesn't give him a chance to show the stuff he did in ''A Tree Grows in Brooklyn''\".<ref name=gazette>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897532/pittsburgh-post-gazette/|title='That Brennan Girl'|author=E. R.|date=December 18, 1946|page=10|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Similarly, ''[[The San Francisco Examiner]]'' commended Dunn for being \"more than adequate in an inadequate role\".<ref name=examiner>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897560/the-san-francisco-examiner/|title=Mona Freeman Scores in 'That Brennan Girl'|first=Hortense|last=Morton|date=December 14, 1946|newspaper=[[The San Francisco Examiner]]|page=12|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> \n\nFreeman's performance received harsher scrutiny in light of the extremes of personality she was required to play. ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' wrote: \n<blockquote>Miss Freeman looks lovely, innocent, and very young, at all times. This is remarkable when you consider that she has to impersonate a thief, a devoted young mother, a brazen mantrap, an industrious housewife, a shoplifter, a war widow, a bar butterfly, a confidence woman and a specimen of fine womanhood, and all within 95 minutes. The only way Republic could get this role played right would be to have [[Katharine Cornell]], [[Helen Hayes]], [[June Havoc]] and [[Ina Claire]] do it in relays. Even then we wouldn't like it.<ref name=bsun>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897273/the-baltimore-sun/|title='Brennan Girl'|first=Donald|last=Kirkley|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=January 18, 1947|page=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' wrote: \"Miss Freeman should get A-plus for her sincere attempt to play a bad girl. Fine features, a sensitive face and a touch of gentleness about her makes it doubtful casting. A tougher brat would have filled the role better\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897173/fort-worth-star-telegram/|title=Social Problem Rates Tawdry, Emotional 'A'|first=Ida Belle|last=Hicks|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=February 26, 1947|page=10| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' panned Freeman's acting as \"immature\".<ref name=gazette/> At the same time, it gave kudos to the performances of actresses [[June Duprez]], Dorothy Vaughn, and [[Rosalind Ivan]], calling the latter's portrayal of the landlady \"excellent\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897532/pittsburgh-post-gazette/|title='That Brennan Girl'|author=E. R.|date=December 18, 1946|page=10|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]'' also singled out actresses who played minor characters \u2013 including the babysitter ([[Shirley Mills]] in an uncredited role<ref name=afi/>), two lonely women, and an assortment of neighbors \u2013 for praise.<ref name=suntele/>\n\nSantell's direction received positive mention in several reviews. The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the film \"reminiscent of the late '20's in direction (by Old-Timer Alfred Santell) and 'feel'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49011446/the-los-angeles-times/|title=Delinquency Drama and 'Rogue' Billed|first=Philip K.|last=Scheuer|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 8, 1946|page=7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]'' complimented Santell's \"minor directorial flourishes\", adding, \"As a matter of fact, his contribution alone puts the picture into the general category of worth seeing\".<ref name=suntele>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48897502/pittsburgh-sun-telegraph/|title=Dunn Film Starts Run|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]|date=December 18, 1946|page=28| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> ''[[The Minneapolis Star]]'' called [[George Antheil]]'s score \"outstanding\".<ref name=minn/>\n\n==Restoration==\nA re-mastered, restored print of ''That Brennan Girl'' by [[Paramount Pictures]], [[The Film Foundation]], and [[Martin Scorsese]] was screened at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA) in February 2018. The screening was the first in a two-part series titled ''Martin Scorsese Presents Republic Rediscovered: New Restorations from Paramount Pictures'', which showcased 30 restored films from the library of [[Republic Pictures]].<ref name=natalie/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.moma.org/calendar/film/3932|title=Film Series|publisher=[[Museum of Modern Art]]|year=2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hayes|first=Dade|title=Martin Scorsese, Paramount Back MoMA Republic Pictures Screening Series|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/martin-scorsese-paramount-back-moma-republic-pictures-screening-series-1202240835/|accessdate=January 14, 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> The restoration was released on the [[Apple TV (software)|Apple TV app]] the following year.<ref name=natalie>{{cite web |url= http://www.film-foundation.org/apple-tv-republic|title=Paramount Releases Martin Scorsese-Curated Republic Pictures Slate for Digital Purchase|first=Natalie|last=Jarvey|date=September 9, 2019|accessdate=April 18, 2020|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\nThe MoMA website calls the film \"[u]naccountably overlooked\" and a \"resonant, formally inventive film\".<ref name=moma/> According to ''[[The Village Voice]]'', the work displays a host of Santell's creative directorial touches, such as \"scenes played in silhouette, in pantomime as the camera watches through a window, on two or three levels of a staircase in a couple of scenes reminiscent of ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]''\".<ref name=village>{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/02/06/restorations-from-republic-pictures-reveal-a-studio-that-got-its-hands-dirty/|title= Restorations From Republic Pictures Reveal a Studio That Got Its Hands Dirty|first=Farran Smith|last=Nehme|date=February 6, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2020|work=[[The Village Voice]]}}</ref> This report concluded that the film demonstrated \"the kind of creativity that once flourished at Republic\".<ref name=village/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0039020|That Brennan Girl}}\n*{{Allmovie title|49251}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|that_brennan_girl}}\n*{{Internet Archive film|that_brennan_girl|That Brennan Girl}}\n\n[[Category:1946 films]]\n[[Category:Melodramas]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Alfred Santell]]\n[[Category:Films scored by George Antheil]]\n[[Category:Republic Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toA Tree Grows in Brooklyn(link changed toA Tree Grows in Brooklyn (1945 film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/That_Brennan_Girl"}
{"title_page": "SurVision Magazine", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file      = \n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = Anatoly Kudryavitsky\n| founder         = Anatoly Kudryavitsky\n| frequency       = biannual\n| category        = [[Literature]]\n| founded       = 2017\n| country         = [[Ireland]]\n| based           = [[Dublin]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.survisionmagazine.com}}\n| issn            = \n}}\n\n'''''SurVision''''' is an international online poetry [[magazine]]. It was founded in March 2017 in Ireland by poet [[Anatoly Kudryavitsky]] as a platform for new Irish and international [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] poetry in English.\n\nIt is a biannual [[magazine]] that publishes [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] [[poetry]] of different trends and schools, which includes [[translation]]s from other languages.\n\nIn its turn, the [[Munich]]-based [[German-language]] Signaturen Magazine announced that they will be publishing their translations of the best poems from SurVision into German.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://signaturen-magazin.de/interview-anatoly-kudryavitsky-engl..html|title=Interview Anatoly Kudryavitsky engl. - Signaturen|first=Kristian E.|last=K\u00fchn|date=|website=signaturen-magazin.de|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nSurVision has been noted for the range of its contributors, which includes both established and new writers from Ireland and elsewhere.\n\nIn his interview, Anatoly Kudryavitsky wrote the following:\n<blockquote>\n\"At SurVision, we appreciate rich language and honed poetic skills. We have a soft spot for poetic experiments, but we believe that such an experiment has to be successful in order to beget publishable texts. The reader will probably notice that we prefer poems that create distinct visual images to abstract Surrealist poems.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/></blockquote>\n\nAccording to the critic Michael S. Begnal, \"SurVision is a press that brings energy and excitement to Irish poetry.\"<ref>Michael S. Begnal. \"Fusion Fission: Surrealism now\". Poetry Ireland Trumpet #8, July 2019, p. 9</ref>\n\n== SurVision Books ==\nIn April 2018, SurVision started their publishing project. The first two publications in the New Poetics series were 34-page chapbooks by [[Noelle Kocot]] and the Irish surrealist poet [[Ciaran O'Driscoll]]. The publisher of both was named as SurVision Books. More chapbooks followed, by the American Surrealist poet [[elin O'Hara Slavick|Elin O'Hara Slavick]] and by Anatoly Kudryavitsky, as well as translated chapbooks by Sergey Biryukov, a Russian experimental poet, and the Italian poet Maria Grazia Calandrone, as well as by the four American winners of James Tate Poetry Prize 2018. In autumn 2018, SurVision Books published a full-size collection by the American Surrealist poet [[George Kalamaras]] and ''Selected Poems'' by the German poet [[Anton G. Leitner]]; in early 2019, chapbooks by the English experimental poet [[Helen Ivory]] and the Irish poets [[John W. Sexton]], Afric McGlinchey and Tim Murphy; in 2020, chapbooks by American Surrealist poets John Bradley and John Thomas Allen and by Irish poets Matthew Geden and [[Tony Bailie]].<ref>[https://www.irishnews.com/arts/2020/02/05/news/co-down-writer-and-irish-news-journalist-wins-international-poetry-prize-1832661/ Co Down writer and Irish News journalist wins international poetry prize. The Irish News, 05.02.2020]</ref> Also in 2020, an anthology of contemporary Russian Surrealist poetry entitled ''MESSAGE-DOOR'' was published; this book contains works by eight Russian poets in English translation.<ref>[http://survisionmagazine.com/books.htm SurVision Books]</ref>\n\n== Notable contributors ==\n*[[Adam Aitken]]\n*[[Peter Boyle (poet)|Peter Boyle]]\n*[[Patrick Chapman]]\n*[[Patrick Deeley]]\n*[[Janet Hamill]]\n*[[Philip Hammial]]\n*[[Helen Ivory]]\n*[[Candice James]]\t\n*[[George Kalamaras]]\n*[[Noelle Kocot]]\t\t\t\n*[[Medbh McGuckian]]\n*[[Mary O'Donnell]]\n*[[Ciaran O'Driscoll]]\n*[[John Olson (poet and writer)|John Olson]]\t\t\t\n*[[Dilys Rose]]\t\n*[[Stuart Ross]]\n*[[John W. Sexton]]\t\n*[[G. C. Waldrep]]\n*[[Les Wicks]]\t\n*[[Dean Young (poet)|Dean Young]]\n\n==Collections of poetry==\n* [[George Kalamaras]], ''That Moment of Wept''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-7-6}}\n* [[Anton G. Leitner]], ''Selected Poems 1981-2015''. Translated from German. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-8-3}}\n\n== Chapbook Series ==\n* [[Noelle Kocot]], ''Humanity''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-0-7}}  \n* [[Ciaran O'Driscoll]], ''The Speaking Trees''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-1-4}}\n* [[elin O'Hara Slavick|Elin O'Hara Slavick]], ''Cameramouth''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-4-5}}\n* Sergey Biryukov, ''Transformations''. Trans. from Russian by Erina Megowan and Anatoly Kudryavitsky {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-5-2}}\n* [[Anatoly Kudryavitsky]], ''Stowaway''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-2-1}}\n* Maria Grazia Calandrone, ''Fossils''. Transl. from Italian. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-6-9}}\n* Christopher Prewitt, ''Paradise Hammer''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-9-0}}\n* Bob Lucky, ''Conversation Starters in the Language No One Speaks''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-00-3}}\n* Anton Yakovlev, ''Chronos Dines Alone''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-01-0}}\n* Mikko Harvey & Jake Bauer, ''Idaho Falls''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-02-7}}\n* [[Helen Ivory]], ''Maps of the Abandoned City''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-04-1}}\n* [[John W. Sexton]], ''Inverted Night''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-05-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://signaturen-magazin.de/interview-anatoly-kudryavitsky-engl..html Editor's interview in Signaturen Magazine]\n* [https://www.pw.org/literary_magazines/survision_magazine SurVision at Poets & Writers Database]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SurVision}}\n[[Category:2017 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Poetry literary magazines]]\n[[Category:English-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Irish literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2017]]\n[[Category:Biannual magazines]]\n[[Category:Media in Dublin (city)]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file      = \n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = Anatoly Kudryavitsky\n| founder         = Anatoly Kudryavitsky\n| frequency       = biannual\n| category        = [[Literature]]\n| founded       = 2017\n| country         = [[Ireland]]\n| based           = [[Dublin]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.survisionmagazine.com}}\n| issn            = \n}}\n\n'''''SurVision''''' is an international online poetry [[magazine]]. It was founded in March 2017 in Ireland by poet [[Anatoly Kudryavitsky]] as a platform for new Irish and international [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] poetry in English.\n\nIt is a biannual [[magazine]] that publishes [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] [[poetry]] of different trends and schools, which includes [[translation]]s from other languages.\n\nIn its turn, the [[Munich]]-based [[German-language]] Signaturen Magazine announced that they will be publishing their translations of the best poems from SurVision into German.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://signaturen-magazin.de/interview-anatoly-kudryavitsky-engl..html|title=Interview Anatoly Kudryavitsky engl. - Signaturen|first=Kristian E.|last=K\u00fchn|date=|website=signaturen-magazin.de|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nSurVision has been noted for the range of its contributors, which includes both established and new writers from Ireland and elsewhere.\n\nIn his interview, Anatoly Kudryavitsky wrote the following:\n<blockquote>\n\"At SurVision, we appreciate rich language and honed poetic skills. We have a soft spot for poetic experiments, but we believe that such an experiment has to be successful in order to beget publishable texts. The reader will probably notice that we prefer poems that create distinct visual images to abstract Surrealist poems.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/></blockquote>\n\nAccording to the critic Michael S. Begnal, \"SurVision is a press that brings energy and excitement to Irish poetry.\"<ref>Michael S. Begnal. \"Fusion Fission: Surrealism now\". Poetry Ireland Trumpet #8, July 2019, p. 9</ref>\n\n== SurVision Books ==\nIn April 2018, SurVision started their publishing project. The first two publications in the New Poetics series were 34-page chapbooks by [[Noelle Kocot]] and the Irish surrealist poet [[Ciaran O'Driscoll]]. The publisher of both was named as SurVision Books. More chapbooks followed, by the American Surrealist poet [[elin O'Hara Slavick|Elin O'Hara Slavick]] and by Anatoly Kudryavitsky, as well as translated chapbooks by Sergey Biryukov, a Russian experimental poet, and the Italian poet Maria Grazia Calandrone, as well as by the four American winners of James Tate Poetry Prize 2018. In autumn 2018, SurVision Books published a full-size collection by the American Surrealist poet [[George Kalamaras]] and ''Selected Poems'' by the German poet [[Anton G. Leitner]]; in early 2019, chapbooks by the English experimental poet [[Helen Ivory]] and the Irish poets [[John W. Sexton]], Afric McGlinchey and Tim Murphy; in 2020, chapbooks by American Surrealist poets John Bradley and John Thomas Allen and by Irish poets Matthew Geden and [[Tony Bailie]].<ref>[https://www.irishnews.com/arts/2020/02/05/news/co-down-writer-and-irish-news-journalist-wins-international-poetry-prize-1832661/ Co Down writer and Irish News journalist wins international poetry prize. Irish News, 05.02.2020]</ref> Also in 2020, an anthology of contemporary Russian Surrealist poetry entitled ''MESSAGE-DOOR'' was published; this book contains works by eight Russian poets in English translation.<ref>[http://survisionmagazine.com/books.htm SurVision Books]</ref>\n\n== Notable contributors ==\n*[[Adam Aitken]]\n*[[Peter Boyle (poet)|Peter Boyle]]\n*[[Patrick Chapman]]\n*[[Patrick Deeley]]\n*[[Janet Hamill]]\n*[[Philip Hammial]]\n*[[Helen Ivory]]\n*[[Candice James]]\t\n*[[George Kalamaras]]\n*[[Noelle Kocot]]\t\t\t\n*[[Medbh McGuckian]]\n*[[Mary O'Donnell]]\n*[[Ciaran O'Driscoll]]\n*[[John Olson (poet and writer)|John Olson]]\t\t\t\n*[[Dilys Rose]]\t\n*[[Stuart Ross]]\n*[[John W. Sexton]]\t\n*[[G. C. Waldrep]]\n*[[Les Wicks]]\t\n*[[Dean Young (poet)|Dean Young]]\n\n==Collections of poetry==\n* [[George Kalamaras]], ''That Moment of Wept''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-7-6}}\n* [[Anton G. Leitner]], ''Selected Poems 1981-2015''. Translated from German. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-8-3}}\n\n== Chapbook Series ==\n* [[Noelle Kocot]], ''Humanity''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-0-7}}  \n* [[Ciaran O'Driscoll]], ''The Speaking Trees''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-1-4}}\n* [[elin O'Hara Slavick|Elin O'Hara Slavick]], ''Cameramouth''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-4-5}}\n* Sergey Biryukov, ''Transformations''. Trans. from Russian by Erina Megowan and Anatoly Kudryavitsky {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-5-2}}\n* [[Anatoly Kudryavitsky]], ''Stowaway''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-2-1}}\n* Maria Grazia Calandrone, ''Fossils''. Transl. from Italian. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-6-9}}\n* Christopher Prewitt, ''Paradise Hammer''. {{ISBN|978-1-9995903-9-0}}\n* Bob Lucky, ''Conversation Starters in the Language No One Speaks''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-00-3}}\n* Anton Yakovlev, ''Chronos Dines Alone''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-01-0}}\n* Mikko Harvey & Jake Bauer, ''Idaho Falls''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-02-7}}\n* [[Helen Ivory]], ''Maps of the Abandoned City''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-04-1}}\n* [[John W. Sexton]], ''Inverted Night''. {{ISBN|978-1-912963-05-8}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://signaturen-magazin.de/interview-anatoly-kudryavitsky-engl..html Editor's interview in Signaturen Magazine]\n* [https://www.pw.org/literary_magazines/survision_magazine SurVision at Poets & Writers Database]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SurVision}}\n[[Category:2017 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Poetry literary magazines]]\n[[Category:English-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Irish literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2017]]\n[[Category:Biannual magazines]]\n[[Category:Media in Dublin (city)]]\n", "name_user": "Bonmot", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SurVision_Magazine"}
